<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Searches for Clay Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Pete Sampras won't just be battling the clay at the  
Italian Open this year. He also has to deal with rust. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras comes to the tournament after four weeks off because of  
a back injury, making his annual quest to succeed on the slow red 
clay that much tougher. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian Open, which begins Monday, features its top men's  
field ever with 29 of the world's top 30 players, and a good week 
here would be a lift for Sampras, whose power game is dulled by 
clay. 
</P>
<P>
	Results on the surface have become hard to predict. No one has  
won more than one clay title this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The French Open starts eight days after Rome wraps up and is the  
only Grand Slam tournament played on clay. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also the only major title Sampras has never won.  
</P>
<P>
	He has 11 Grand Slam titles, one short of Roy Emerson's record,  
with five at Wimbledon, four at the U.S. Open, and two at the 
Australian Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras skipped this year's Australian, in January, citing  
fatigue after playing a string of tournaments at the end of 1998 to 
ensure he would retain the No. 1 ranking for a record sixth 
straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	He pulled out of the Barcelona, Spain, clay event in mid-April  
with an aching back and has not played since. 
</P>
<P>
	Yevgeny Kafelnikov capitalized, taking the title at Melbourne --  
even thanking Sampras for staying home -- and eventually sliding 
into the top slot in the rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Russian, who won at Roland Garros in 1996, has not been  
playing like the world's best. He has lost seven straight matches 
since February. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras did manage to win the Italian Open in 1994, beating  
Boris Becker in the final. Since then, the American has tumbled out 
in the first round twice and in the round of 16 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Kafelnikov, along with the last two French Open champions,  
Carlos Moya and Gustavo Kuerten, should pose a threat to Sampras. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcelo Rios will be back to defend his Italian Open crown, but  
the diminutive Chilean has struggled with injuries all year. He's 
without a title in 1999 and his ranking, which briefly reached No. 
1 last year, has slipped to No. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	And Andre Agassi, twice a finalist at the French Open, could  
again resurrect his game long enough to make a good run. He was 
among the first men in Rome, arriving Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
