<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 02:32:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sailor Gets Kick to Finish Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. -- A booming cannon and three red flares marked  
the end of the grueling 27,000-mile Around Alone sailing race for 
winner Giovanni Solidni. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian sailor lit a white flare and danced on the deck of  
his yacht Fila while dozens of boaters cheered him on the last two 
miles of the race that began in September and ended at 1:32 a.m. 
EDT today. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldini, the first non-Frenchman to win the race in the five  
times it has been held, had been at the mercy of a high pressure 
and low winds the past few days, crawling along at 6 to 8 knots. 
</P>
<P>
	But he finished with a flourish, making about 15 knots on a  
brisk southwest wind. 
</P>
<P>
	His father, Adolfo, members of his crew and race officials  
clamored aboard the boat along with Italian reporters to welcome 
Soldini. 
</P>
<P>
	He finished in record time despite the delay of the last few  
days. His unofficial time of 117 days was more than four days 
faster than the previous record set by Christophe Auguin in 1991 
when the race was known as the BOC Challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Frenchman Marc Thiercelin, with the only other 60-foot boat  
still in the race, was about 250 miles behind Soldini, but more 
than 11 days back in the overall standings. He was expected to 
finish late Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the smaller, 50-foot boat division, Mike Garside led  
Frenchman J.P. Mouligne by about 285 miles and was about 690 miles 
from the finish late Friday. Mouligne won the three previous legs 
and is the apparent winner of the division. 
</P>
<P>
	The skippers were among 16 boats that left Charleston last  
September for the race that included stopovers in Cape Town, South 
Africa; Auckland, New Zealand; and Punta del Este, Uruguay. 
</P>
<P>
	The highlight of Soldini's race was a daring rescue of French  
sailor Isabelle Autissier in the frigid, rolling waters of the 
Southern Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	Autissier's yacht PRB was sailing in 20-knot winds when the  
automatic pilot malfunctioned. The boat turned on its side and then 
flipped completely. 
</P>
<P>
	The vessel was suppose to right itself, but it never did and  
Autissier had only seconds to close the watertight hatch of the 
cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	She settled down to wait for rescue as Soldini battled for 200  
miles through 40 mph winds and waves as high as 30 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	He found the overturned yacht, but saw no sign of Autissier. But  
then he tossed a hammer at the hull and she quickly emerged from an 
escape hatch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
