<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ottke Defends His IBF Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- Germany's Sven Ottke defended his  
IBF super middleweight title for the second time Saturday with a 
unanimous decision over Gabriel Hernandez. 
</P>
<P>
	Ottke (15-0) controlled the fight from the first round against  
the Dominican Republic fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	The light-hitting 31-year-old Ottke, who has just three  
knockouts, floored Hernandez in the opening seconds but Hernandez 
came back. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the sixth, Hernandez began to slow down noticeably and  
Ottke began to toy with him, fighting with his hands down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 17:12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Protesters Rail Vs. Embassy Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Protests at the U.S. and British embassies in  
Beijing that began with well-organized ranks of student 
demonstrators later turned into a rowdy mob that threw rocks and 
tried to set cars on fire. Many carried banners and handwritten 
signs condemning the NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in 
Yugoslavia. They shouted ``Down with the Yankees'' and ``Protect 
sovereignty and peace.'' Not since the government crushed democracy 
protests at Tiananmen Square on June 4, 1989, have students and 
other Chinese marched through Beijing streets in large numbers with 
banners and slogans. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole Faults Clinton in Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful  
Elizabeth Dole today said the Clinton administration has made 
fundamental strategic and tactical blunders in the Balkan bombing 
effort. Those mistakes, she said, are fair game in the presidential 
campaign. Mrs. Dole said the effort is being run largely by 
politicians and not soldiers, and they have made errors in 
targeting, intensity and focus. Competing politicians traditionally 
have remained quiet during an overseas combat operation, to avoid 
sending conflicting signals to enemies. But Mrs. Dole said the 
stakes in the Balkans are too high for candidates to stay silent. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Surveys Tornado Damage  
</P>
<P>
	DEL CITY, Okla. (AP) -- Following an aerial tour of the outskirts  
of Oklahoma City today, President Clinton said he's never seen so 
much destruction over such a wide area. The president promised up 
to $12.5 million to provide temporary jobs for victims of the 
deadly tornadoes that leveled entire neighborhoods and killed at 
least 50 people this past week in Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas and 
Tennessee. Half of the funds will immediately be made available to 
put 3,500 Oklahomans and 600 Kansans to work. Clinton also said he 
would ask Congress for an additional $372 million for FEMA's 
disaster relief fund. 

</P>
<P>
	Gun Industry Eyes Gun-Control  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leaders of two major firearms industry groups  
want to see what the Clinton Administration has to offer before 
signing on to its gun-control proposals. ``We haven't seen the 
language,'' said Robert Ricker, executive director of the National 
Shooting Sports Foundation. The crunch comes Monday at a White 
House strategy session on children, violence and responsibility. 
Ricker said the industry has supported versions of some of the 
White House proposals in the past. Such laws became the subject of 
much discussion after two teen-agers shot 13 people, then killed 
themselves, in Littleton, Colo. last month. 

</P>
<P>
	Parents Back Gun Restrictions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Parents whose children have been injured or  
killed by guns today pledged to make Mother's Day a day of 
political action. Joined by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton at 
the White House, four parents shared stories about their children 
to about 300 guests, many also parents of shooting victims. ``How 
many more Springfields or Littletons can we suffer before we do 
what must be done to keep guns away from children?'' asked Rebecca 
Lynn. She sat beside her daughter, Betina, who was wounded in last 
May's shooting at Thurston High School in Springfield, Ore. 

</P>
<P>
	Citadel Graduates First Female  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- The first female cadet in the Citadel's  
history graduated from the military school today, ending a 
150-year-old, male-only tradition following a federal court fight. 
Nancy Ruth Mace, a magna cum laude graduate in business 
administration, received her degree from her father, Emory Mace, 
the school's commandant of cadets. She was greeted with applause as 
she accepted the degree. There had been some hissing during a 
ceremony earlier in the school year when she received her senior 
class ring. 

</P>
<P>
	Reprieve Possible in Pizza Killings  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A man who received the death penalty for  
gunning down a pizza deliveryman in 1997 has been given a possible 
reprieve. Judge Reginald Stanton on Friday ordered Thomas 
Koskovich's death sentence to be commuted to life in prison if he's 
still alive five years from now. Stanton believes inmates unfairly 
spend too much time on death row. Defense attorneys say to their 
knowledge, such an order has never been issued at the trial court 
level. Prosecutors say Stanton exceeded his authority. 

</P>
<P>
	Trail Blazers Beat Suns 95-85  
</P>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Isaiah Rider scored 25 points and the  
Portland Trail Blazers pulled away in the latter part of the fourth 
quarter to beat the Phoenix Suns 95-85 today in the first game of 
their best-of-five series. Brian Grant had 16 points and 10 
rebounds, and Arvydas Sabonis added 12 points, eight rebounds, 
eight assists and three blocks for the Blazers, who are trying to 
make it out of the first round for the first time since advancing 
to the 1992 NBA Finals. Jason Kidd had 17 points and seven assists 
for Phoenix. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
