<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tribe's Comeback Defies Logic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Did that really happen?  
</P>
<P>
	That was a frequently asked question Saturday morning at Jacobs  
Field as fans and players were still digesting all the numbers from 
Cleveland's dizzying 20-11 win over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on 
Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians overcame deficits of 9-1 and 10-2 by scoring 18 runs  
in their final three at-bats for Cleveland's 20th -- and most 
memorable -- win this season. 
</P>
<P>
	How many times have you seen a team down by eight runs win by  
nine? 
</P>
<P>
	``Ah, never,'' said Travis Fryman, whose three-run homer in the  
seventh inning pulled the Indians to 11-9. 
</P>
<P>
	In a three-inning span from the sixth to eighth innings, the  
Indians sent 33 batters to the plate and collected 16 hits. They 
scored four runs in the sixth and seven in both the seventh and 
eighth innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this team, you never know what might happen,'' said David  
Justice, who homered twice and drove in five runs as the Indians 
recorded their ninth come-from-behind win this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the many numbers posted and records set, the most  
interesting were: 
</P>
<P>
	-- 34 combined hits  
</P>
<P>
	-- 31 runs scored (a new stadium record).  
</P>
<P>
	-- 14 extra-base hits (six homers, seven doubles, one triple)  
</P>
<P>
	-- 19 runners left on base  
</P>
<P>
	-- 89 baseballs used.  
</P>
<P>
	Justice's second homer, a three-run shot in the sixth, closed  
the gap to 10-6 and had the Indians' bench and 40,601 fans 
believing Cleveland could win. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Justice had a premonition the Indians might be up to  
something special. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said to Paul Wagner to just hold them right there, because  
you never know what's going to happen,'' Justice said. ``I swear, 
10 minutes later, the score was 10-10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Tampa Bay, the collapse helped the Devil Rays set or tie 11  
club records and continued a strange run of recent events. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 1, Devil Rays manager Larry Rothschild asked umpire Larry  
Barnett to check Detroit pitcher Brian Moehler's glove. Moehler was 
discovered to have sandpaper and, after he was ejected, the Devil 
Rays rallied to win. 
</P>
<P>
	The next day, Jose Canseco hit a fly ball at Tropicana Field  
that lodged in the stadium's catwalk. Earlier this week, the Devil 
Rays blew a 3-0 lead in the ninth inning and lost 5-3 to Kansas 
City, and then combined with the Royals the next night to hit eight 
homers in a three-inning span. 
</P>
<P>
	But those paled in comparison to Friday night's fiasco.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everything that could go wrong did,'' losing pitcher Jim Mecir  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
