<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A nurse accused in the deaths of  
more than 100 patients in the past four months may have killed them 
to collect commissions from local funeral homes, media reported 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Edson Izidoro Guimaraes was arrested Friday in Rio de Janeiro.  
He has admitted killing ``five or six'' patients but denies profit 
was his motive. 
</P>
<P>
	Guimaraes says he only wanted to ease patients suffering by  
taking away oxygen masks or giving lethal injections at Salgado 
Filho Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did it to those in irreversible comas and whose families  
were suffering,'' the 42-year-old trauma ward nurse told TV Globo 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	But police are investigating several Rio funeral homes after  
Guimaraes told reporters he received commissions in exchange for 
death certificate information -- between $60-$600 per certificate. 
Such information gives morticians a head start in contacting the 
victim's family about funeral arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico City police have arrested nine people  
who kidnapped, robbed and sometimes raped tourists hailing taxis 
near the airport, the city attorney general's office said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven men and two women operated for more than a year, the  
office said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	One member would drive a green Volkswagen Beetle cab, which are  
common in the city, and signal to his accomplices when a passenger 
was believed to have money. The accomplices would then climb into 
the cab and rob passengers of valuables. 
</P>
<P>
	One gang member said he sometimes took female victims to his  
residence and raped them, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robberies of taxi passengers have become common in Mexico City  
in recent years, and the U.S. embassy has warned tourists not to 
hail cabs in the street. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A group of independence activists  
camped on a beach with unexploded munitions Saturday at a U.S. Navy 
bombing range, protesting an accidental blast that killed a 
security guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ruben Berrios, leader of the Puerto Rican Independence  
Party, and 100 others took boats to the beach on Vieques Island and 
set up a half dozen small tents. 
</P>
<P>
	Berrios said protesters would remain until the Navy pulls out.  
</P>
<P>
	The April 19 death of David Sanes Rodriguez has given new  
impetus to decades of demands that the Navy withdraw from Vieques. 
He died when a U.S. F-18 missed a target and dropped a bomb near an 
observation tower. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1940, the Navy has controlled two-thirds of the  
33,000-acre island east of Puerto Rico's main island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
