<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wis. Court May Decide Own Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- The justices of the Wisconsin Supreme Court  
started this fight -- and they might just decide the victor. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices filed a lawsuit in 1997 claiming they were wrongly  
denied a pay raise approved by the state Legislature. A state 
agency had ruled the money couldn't be paid because it would raise 
the justices' wage above that of the governor, which is not allowed 
under state law. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor's salary had also been adjusted upward, but the  
increase did not become effective until last January. In the 
meantime, the justices' pay rose higher than his. 
</P>
<P>
	A trial court sided with the justices, but the state appealed.  
Now the matter is headed to the Supreme Court, where the conflict 
of interest is plain. 
</P>
<P>
	A state appeals court suggested that the Supreme Court use  
reserve judges to hear the case. But state Courts Director J. Denis 
Moran said the suggestion won't fly. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no provision for the temporary assignment of anybody  
to the Supreme Court,'' he said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court clerk said the justices could decide  
within 30 to 60 days whether to take the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctrine of necessity says if there is no other forum  
available to resolve a dispute, the court can even take it in the 
face if what appears to be conflict,'' said Moran. ``However it is 
handled, it will have to be a little bit creative.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
