<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers' Miller Set for Playoffs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- It's playoff time -- and that means Reggie  
Miller has another opportunity to add to his list of heroics. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller and his Indiana Pacers teammates, who took Chicago to  
seven games before being eliminated in the Eastern Conference 
finals last year, begin their best-of-5 first-round series Sunday 
against Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller's nine previous trips to the playoffs have been filled  
with dramatic game-winning shots and his 23.5 scoring average for 
65 playoff games includes two 39-point performances. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those games came in Game 5 of the 1994 Eastern Conference  
finals against the New York Knicks in Madison Square Garden. With 
the series tied 2-2, Miller tormented the hostile New York crowd by 
hitting five 3-pointers and tallying 25 points in the fourth 
quarter as Indiana upset the Knicks 93-86. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not afraid to fail,'' said backcourt mate Mark Jackson.  
``All the great ones, that's the key, they're not afraid to miss 
the shot and they step into it with confidence. He actually 
believes, and he's disappointed when the game is on the line and he 
doesn't do something heroic. He's a special player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pacers forward Antonio Davis said nothing Miller does in the  
playoffs surprises him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm like a fan. I keep looking for that fantastic play, that  
last-second shot,'' Davis said. ``Hopefully, this year we won't put 
him in too many situations like that. I think that's putting too 
much pressure on one guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana hasn't played since Tuesday and the Pacers have  
capitalized on the time off with three days of intensive practices 
that each lasted two or more hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really cleaned up a lot of things that we were lacking at  
times,'' Davis said. ``The greatest thing is our focus. We've 
really been focusing on correcting mistakes, and playing great 
defense, which we will need to do against a team like this that can 
really flat out outscore us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee compiled the leading field goal percentage in the  
Eastern Conference, averaging 46 percent, and led the league in 
3-point shooting. However, the Bucks were swept by Indiana in three 
games this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems that Indiana doesn't give us much respect, and (the  
media) doesn't want to give us much respect,'' said Bucks coach 
George Karl. ``I think we're a lot closer to them that you all 
(media) say we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karl, who guided Milwaukee into the playoffs in his first year  
coaching the Bucks, believes his team can produce an upset. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're one of the few teams that aren't afraid to try to  
outshoot them,'' Karl said. ``We're going to try to play fast. It's 
anti-playoff. Playoffs are usually not fast-paced games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Karl is confident, he admits Miller will be a problem.  
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be as bothersome to him as possible,'' Karl said.  
``We have to control his shots, contest his catches, be very 
aggressive with him and switch players. We can't expect Ray Allen 
to be the only guy to do it,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
