<HEADLINE> Cops Nab Man They Call Bike Bandit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- A man called the bicycle bandit had held up  
at least five banks in central Illinois, always making his getaway 
on two wheels. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, police say they've got their man and his bicycle. They also  
got his wife, their two cars and their two young children. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a man wearing a baseball cap and wraparound  
sunglasses pedaled up to the Associated Bank and ordered a teller 
to give him cash. He then stuffed $19,629 into his backpack and 
pedaled away. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, however, a policeman spotted him and gave chase.  
</P>
<P>
	Officer Ken Tegard said he followed as the bike bandit sped to a  
parked car to meet his wife. The cyclist put the bike in the trunk 
of his wife's car, tossed a pellet gun into the back of a nearby 
pickup truck, then drove away in one direction in a Jeep while his 
wife drove the car off in another direction. 
</P>
<P>
	A swarm of patrol cars cornered Rodney Henninger, 29, and his  
wife, Judi, 23. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple's two small children were along for a ride in one of  
the two getaway vehicles, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple were ordered held without bail, pending a hearing  
Monday on federal charges of armed bank robbery. If convicted, they 
face up to 25 years in prison and a $250,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	According to court records, Henninger admitted robbing three  
banks in Bloomington and two more in LaSalle since October. Police 
believe he also robbed seven other banks in Bloomington, Normal, 
Peru and Champaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
