<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes Tornado Victim Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- On his way to view the damage wrought by deadly  
tornadoes in Oklahoma, President Clinton today announced a $12 
million program to provide temporary jobs to residents of the 
storm-ravaged area around Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he would seek an additional $372 million from  
Congress for a federal disaster relief fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was taking a half-hour helicopter tour of the area today  
before meeting residents in the hard-hit area of Del City, Okla. 
Storms in Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas and Tennessee killed more than 50 
people over the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing I've learned is that the images we see on  
television can never fully convey the level of sheer destruction or 
the depth of human grief caused by these disasters,'' the president 
said in his weekly radio address, which was taped after a 
fund-raising stop in Houston on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Labor Department would spend more than $12 million  
to provide temporary jobs to 3,500 Oklahomans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Men and women who lost their jobs in businesses destroyed by  
the tornadoes will be paid to serve at relief centers, to 
distribute food and water, to help on construction crews,'' the 
president said. ``They'll be able to feed their families by 
rebuilding their communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president, who raised $700,000 for Democrats at fund-raising  
events in Houston and Austin, Texas, on Friday, has already 
declared disaster areas in Oklahoma, Texas and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	He took the occasion of his visit to the Oklahoma City area to  
press Congress to approve $10 million in his proposed fiscal 2000 
budget to improve the National Weather Service's next generation of 
Doppler radar. 
</P>
<P>
	Warning times for tornadoes have been improving, Clinton said,  
but an improved Doppler system was still needed. ``This system 
makes it possible to issue warnings in advance of coming tornadoes 
so that local residents can seek shelter,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also said he would ask Congress for an additional $372  
million for the Federal Emergency Management Agency's disaster 
relief fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``These resources are crucial for our disaster relief efforts  
and I urge Congress to act quickly on my request,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, the president emphasized how tough times bring  
communities together. 
</P>
<P>
	``Natural disasters test our faith. But they also show us that  
the old-fashioned American values of neighborly care and concern 
are still very much alive,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
