<HEADLINE> 2 Gun Groups May Back Clinton Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two firearms industry groups have agreed to  
support some of the Clinton administration's new gun-control 
proposals, The Washington Post reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them are measures raising the age eligibility for buying a  
handgun from 18 to 21, holding parents criminally responsible for 
allowing children access to guns and forbidding juveniles convicted 
of violent felonies from ever buying a gun, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of the groups -- the American Shooting Sports Council and  
the National Shooting Sports Council -- also agreed on measures 
requiring people who sell guns at gun shows to make background 
checks on the buyers, the Post said. 
</P>
<P>
	But it said the organizations refused to endorse White House  
proposals to require three-day waiting periods for buying guns and 
allowing people to buy only one gun a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement came at a meeting Tuesday at the White House  
between Bruce Reed, President Clinton's domestic policy adviser, 
and leaders of the two gun industry groups, the Post said. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association, which did not attend, plans to  
unveil its own package of proposals on Monday to counter Clinton's 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert A. Ricker, executive director of the American Shooting  
Sports Council, told the Post that the recent high school massacre 
in Littleton, Colo., has spurred people on both sides of the 
gun-control debate to seek solutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
