<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs' Duncan To Up Intensity  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tim Duncan didn't know quite what to expect  
in his first postseason last year. Now he's wiser -- and more 
emotional. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan's top-seeded San Antonio Spurs face the No. 8 Minnesota  
Timberwolves in a best-of-5 Western Conference series starting 
Sunday in the Alamodome. 
</P>
<P>
	``Walking in last year I really didn't know what to expect,'' he  
said. ``I'm pretty much going to go out and do the same thing I've 
been doing. I'm going to turn up the intensity a little bit. You 
know it counts for more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Minnesota has beaten the Spurs twice this season,  
the Timberwolves know that accomplishing it in the playoffs will be 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	This is a different San Antonio team than the one they defeated  
early in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can limit those guys shooting-wise, you give yourselves  
a chance. That's where you have to start,'' said Timberwolves coach 
Flip Saunders. ``They're playing extremely well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two teams split their regular-season series 2-2, with each  
team getting victories on their home courts. Both of Minnesota's 
victories came early in February, when the Spurs were only 6-8. 
</P>
<P>
	The Timberwolves found a way to contain Duncan during the wins  
with physical play. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've done a great job on Tim,'' said Spurs coach Gregg  
Popovich. ``They play good defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan expects more heavy guarding from Minnesota on Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've got some big bodies down there, some very physical  
bodies down there, and they give me a bit of a problem,'' Duncan 
said. ``But hopefully I'll get rolling early and stay away from a 
whole lot of the banging and the double-teaming and make them pay 
for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Duncan-David Robinson duo led the Spurs down the stretch,  
giving San Antonio the Midwest Division title and the top seed 
throughout the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final four games, San Antonio beat Portland twice plus  
Utah and Golden State. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Utah and San Antonio finished the regular season at 37-13,  
but the Spurs beat the Jazz 2-1 in the their regular-season series 
to take the top playoff spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Timberwolves forward Kevin Garnett knows he'll have his work cut  
out for him with Duncan and fellow seven-footer, Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	``They bring a whole 'nother look to the game, so to speak. If  
you get past one, there's another one,'' Garnett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota is still adjusting to a squad that has changed over  
the season after trading point guard Stephon Marbury. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs haven't faced the Timberwolves with Terrell Brandon in  
the lineup because he sat out his only game against Minnesota 
Brandon was out with a thigh injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only does San Antonio have the edge in talent, they also  
have more playoff experience after adding Mario Elie, Jerome Kersey 
and Steve Kerr. 
</P>
<P>
	``It adds to everybody's confidence, without a doubt,'' Popovich  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
