<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:52:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Tours Tornado-Ravaged Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEL CITY, Okla. (AP) -- As residents rooted through the rubble of  
their homes, President Clinton on Saturday took in the devastation 
wrought by killer tornadoes and promised millions in federal aid 
for rebuilding efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been going to these sites for 20 years,'' said Clinton,  
a former Arkansas governor. ``This is the most devastating tornado 
I have ever seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Residents waved American flags and cheered as the president's  
motorcade rolled through a Del City neighborhood where the twisters 
had uprooted trees, overturned cars and leveled houses. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms killed at least 50 people in Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas and  
Tennessee and injured hundreds more this past week. More than 9,000 
homes were destroyed in the greater Oklahoma City area and more 
than 8,500 buildings in Kansas were severely damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton already has declared major disaster areas in the hardest  
hit spots, making them eligible for emergency funds to pay for 
cleanup and temporary housing. He promised up to $12 million more 
in relief. 
</P>
<P>
	On a walking tour, Clinton stopped to chat with David and Alicia  
Price. The couple is expecting their first child and were concerned 
about where they will live now that their home had been destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton signed a mortarboard for Price, who was receiving a  
master's degree Saturday from Oklahoma State University. ``You're 
young and you're going to have a baby,'' Clinton said. ``It's all 
right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Across the street, Tammy Weston waited by a mint green chair  
that was spared by the storm. ``I thank you,'' Weston said, as 
Clinton wrapped an arm around her shoulder. ``It means a lot to us 
that you came.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arriving at Tinker Air Force Base, Clinton went directly to a  
briefing with James Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency 
Management Agency, Gov. Frank Keating and officials from other 
state, local and federal relief agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in nearby Moore, Okla., hundreds of relief workers  
labored under a searing sun to sort through truckloads of donated 
food, clothing and other items that will be delivered to those 
recovering from the tornadoes. They paused when Clinton flew 
overhead by helicopter to survey the damage. 
</P>
<P>
	On the 25-minute aerial tour, Clinton saw subdivision after  
shattered subdivision recognizable only by the heaps of rubble at 
the ends of driveways where houses once stood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never seen so much complete destruction of homes over  
so wide an area,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the situation, Keating said there had been no incidents  
of looting reported. ``This is a real tribute to Oklahomans,'' 
Clinton replied. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton first announced the new relief funds in his weekly radio  
address. He said the Labor Department would spend up to $12.5 
million to provide temporary jobs for tornado victims. Half of the 
funds, provided under the Job Training Partnership Act, will 
immediately be made available to put 3,500 Oklahomans and 600 
Kansans to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also said he would ask Congress for an additional $372  
million for FEMA's disaster relief fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, the Small Business Administration was providing  
low-interest loans to displaced homeowners and businesses. 
Homeowners are eligible for up to $200,000 in loans; businesses up 
to $1.5 million. The Internal Revenue Service also has suspended 
collections in the affected areas for 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also used the visit to press Congress to approve $10  
million in his proposed fiscal 2000 budget to improve the National 
Weather Service's next generation of Doppler radar. Warning times 
for tornadoes have been improving, but Clinton said a better 
Doppler system was still needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
