<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UN Expresses Regret Over China Blast  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council, summoned by China  
for an emergency meeting early Saturday, said they were shocked and 
concerned by the damage and casualties caused by an apparent NATO 
missile strike on China's Embassy in Belgrade. The council noted 
that NATO had already launched an investigation into the incident, 
and that NATO and the United States had expressed regret. 

</P>
<P>
	China Outraged Over Embassy Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China reacted with outrage today to the bombing  
of its embassy in Yugoslavia, with the government accusing NATO of 
a ``barbarian act'' and ordinary Chinese calling on Beijing to send 
in troops. At least three people were killed and more than 20 
injured when NATO missiles struck the embassy in Belgrade, the 
state-run Xinhua News Agency said. One person was missing. NATO 
said it did not intentionally target the embassy. Apparently 
worried that public anger over the attack might spark protests, 
police beefed up security outside the U.S. Embassy in Beijing. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Official Nixes British Trip  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov called off a  
trip to Britain for talks on the Kosovo crisis today amid reports 
that Moscow was angry after NATO bombs damaged the Chinese Embassy 
in Belgrade. Russia's special envoy to the Yugoslav conflict, 
ex-premier Viktor Chernomyrdin, said he would not postpone a trip 
to several European countries beginning today. Chernomyrdin planned 
to fly to Germany first and also visit several other European 
capitals, including Belgrade, to follow up on a proposed peace plan 
worked out by the Western powers and Russia. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Gun Groups May Back Clinton Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two firearms industry groups have agreed to  
support some of the Clinton administration's new gun-control 
proposals, The Washington Post has reported. Among them are 
measures raising the age eligibility for buying a handgun from 18 
to 21, holding parents criminally responsible for allowing children 
access to guns and forbidding juveniles convicted of violent 
felonies from ever buying a gun. Leaders of the groups -- the 
American Shooting Sports Council and the National Shooting Sports 
Council -- also agreed on measures requiring people who sell guns at 
gun shows to make background checks on the buyers, the Post said. 

</P>
<P>
	Gov't Arrests Pakistan Journalist  
</P>
<P>
	LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- A dozen police stormed the home of a  
magazine owner today and arrested him, in the latest attack on 
journalists in Pakistan, witnesses said. Police broke down the 
outside gate of Najam Sethi's home in the Punjab provincial capital 
of Lahore, his wife Jugnoo Mohsin said. Sethi owns a weekly 
English-language news magazine, The Friday Times. The newspaper has 
been critical of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's government and Sethi 
has issued public statements saying he feared being arrested. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Makes Historic Romania Visit  
</P>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Pope John Paul II, saying the ``spring  
of hope has begun,'' joined the leader of Romania's Orthodox Church 
in calling for the healing of divisions within Christianity. The 
pope, arriving in the Romanian capital yesterday, said he hoped his 
three-day visit would help ``heal the wounds'' in Catholic-Orthodox 
relations caused by the persecution of Catholics under Romania's 
communist regime, which was deposed in 1989. ``Thank the Lord that 
after the terrible winter of communist reign, the spring of hope 
has begun,'' the pope said in perfect Romanian, to the delight of 
hundreds of people who turned out to greet him on his arrival in 
the Romanian capital. John Paul's visit is the first by a Roman 
pontiff to a mainly Orthodox country in nearly 1,000 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Ship Carriers To Remain in NY, NJ  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Two of the world's largest shipping lines  
have decided to stay in the New York-New Jersey harbor -- a move 
that may help solve a nasty feud that still threatens the port's 
future. Ending a yearlong saga, Sea-Land Service and Maersk 
announced yesterday that economic reasons would keep them in the 
Port of New York and New Jersey. The giant shipping companies 
solicited proposals from other East Coast cities, including 
Baltimore and Halifax, Nova Scotia. Maersk President Tommy Thomsen 
also cited Gov. Christie Whitman's last-minute offer of $120 
million in state funding to reimburse the shippers as crucial to 
the decision. 

</P>
<P>
	Jordan Ends Talks With Hornets  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Michael Jordan said yesterday he pulled  
out of negotiations to buy 50 percent of the Charlotte Hornets 
after owner George Shinn would not agree to giving Jordan complete 
control of the NBA franchise. Money was irrelevant to the 
disagreement, Jordan said. The breakdown was over who would call 
the shots, Jordan told The Charlotte Observer in an interview. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
