<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bratt: Hollywood Unfair to Races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Actor Benjamin Bratt says Hollywood still has a  
long way to go to fairly represent minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea of fair and equal representation for people of color  
in this business is a joke,'' says Bratt, who is of Peruvian and 
German descent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bratt and his brother, Peter, have begun producing their own  
films to bring more minority viewpoints to the screen. One of them, 
``Follow Me Home,'' premiered in 1996 at the Sundance Film 
Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Bratt feels pessimistic because ``the personification of  
this industry is an overpampered, self-satisfied middle-aged white 
male whose only contact with people of color is the people who 
clean his house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bratt, who plays a detective on the NBC series ``Law &AMP; Order,''  
has high praise for girlfriend Julia Roberts, but says dating her 
has created a paradox. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a man who covets my privacy, and I'm going out with the  
most famous actress in the world,'' he says in US magazine's June 
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
