<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vision and Verse Wins Ill. Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STICKNEY, Ill. (AP) -- Vision and Verse rallied through the  
stretch Saturday to beat Prime Directive by 1 1/4 lengths in the 
$500,000 Illinois Derby at Hawthorne Race Course. 
</P>
<P>
	Vision and Verse, ridden by Herberto Castillo Jr., ran past  
favored Yankee Victor in the stretch and then beat Prime Directive 
to the wire. Pineaff closed from last at the head of the stretch to 
finish third in the field of 10 3-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	Certain, the second choice in the betting, wound up last in the  
1 1/8-mile race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a bit of a rough trip going around the first turn,''  
Castillo said. ``I tried to get my colt to relax. He was really on 
the bridle, but I was actually glad to see that because he's the 
kind of horse you have to ask.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vision and Verse went 1 1/8 miles in 1:48 2-5 to earn $300,000 and  
paid $37.20, $15.40 and $11. Prime Directive was worth $6.20 and 
$4.60 and Pineaff returned $6.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Vision and Verse, owned by W. Bruce Lunsford of Louisville, Ky.,  
and trained by Bill Mott, won for the third time in six starts this 
year. It was his first stakes victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Derby is usually run at nearby Sportsmen's Park,  
but construction of an auto racing track there forced the track to 
hold its meeting at Hawthorne this spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
