<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 06:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report Explores Gambling Pros, Cons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearing the end of two years' effort, a  
federal commission on gambling is struck by the amount of work 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	A draft report says the ``most startling and unexpected  
conclusion'' of the National Gambling Impact Study Commission is 
how little is known about the gambling industry's economic and 
social impact. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found that many state and local governments, and Indian  
nations, were prepared to further expand gambling activities, as 
they had already, with a shocking lack of knowledge about the 
impact on their own citizens,'' said the draft report, which is 
subject to change. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft report calls gambling addiction a significant problem  
and youth gambling ``startling.'' It also depicts casinos as a 
uniquely effective economic tool, particularly for Indian tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft report, totaling 283 pages, was released this week  
after the General Services Administration instructed the commission 
it was a public document. Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., a commission 
critic, had asked the GSA to look into whether the commission was 
wrong in keeping the draft private. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the draft chapters already have been changed, and there  
will be further additions and revisions before the commission 
submits the report to Congress on June 18. A hotly debated 
recommendation, added to the report since the drafts were written, 
urges state, local and tribal governments to consider imposing 
moratoriums on gambling expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as a work in progress, however, the draft provides  
indications of where the commission is headed after two years' 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	In most places, the draft report reads more like an encyclopedia  
than an opinion. But on some topics, the report takes strong 
positions: 
</P>
<P>
	--On youth gambling: ``The conclusion is startling but confirmed  
by every study: Our children are gamblers. They gamble before 
leaving high school. As adolescents, they participate in lotteries 
and other forms of gambling that are illegal in most states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--On advertising practices of state lotteries: ``Many  
advertisements emphasize luck over hard work, instant gratification 
over prudent investment and entertainment over savings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--On the relevant research the commission found on gambling: ``As  
a commission we found insufficient data on gambling's overall 
impact on unemployment, property crime, murder, suicide, 
indebtedness, bankruptcy, business disruption or family breakups.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the positive side, the draft report finds casinos to be ``an  
important source of entertainment, jobs and income.'' It 
distinguishes traditional casinos from what the commission 
considers a more worrisome trend, proliferation of ``convenience 
gambling'' in the form of slot machines or video terminals in 
neighborhood stores or restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, a draft chapter on Indian gambling concludes that tribal  
casinos play an essential role in economic development on 
reservations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Federal policy-makers have sought for generations to identify  
means (other than gaming) to advance Indian economies, with a 
notable lack of success,'' the draft chapter says. ``There was no 
evidence presented to the commission suggesting any viable approach 
to economic development across the broad spectrum of Indian 
country, in the absence of gaming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The draft report was written by the commission's staff. When the  
commission's nine members met in Washington recently to review the 
draft, many complained their proposals had been omitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Some commissioners also objected that the report seemed biased  
against gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner and gambling proponent John Wilhelm, general  
president of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Union, 
said the drafts were one-sided because they failed to recognize the 
economic benefits that gambling brings to communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 07:04:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pope Makes Historic Romania Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Pope John Paul II, saying the ``spring  
of hope has begun,'' joined the leader of Romania's Orthodox Church 
in calling for the healing of divisions within Christianity. 
</P>
<P>
	The pope, arriving in the Romanian capital on Friday, said he  
hoped his three-day visit would help ``heal the wounds'' in 
Catholic-Orthodox relations caused by the persecution of Catholics 
under Romania's communist regime, which was deposed in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank the Lord that after the terrible winter of communist  
reign, the spring of hope has begun,'' the pope said in perfect 
Romanian, to the delight of hundreds of people who turned out to 
greet him on his arrival in the Romanian capital. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul's visit is the first by a Roman pontiff to a mainly  
Orthodox country in nearly 1,000 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The pope and Patriarch Teoctist embraced at the airport, and the  
Romanian Orthodox leader stood beside him in the glass-enclosed 
popemobile on the drive into the city. It was believed to be the 
first time the Vatican had invited a non-Catholic clergyman to ride 
with the pope. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Orthodox cathedral, they prayed together -- the  
78-year-old John Paul hunched over, the 84-year patriarch standing 
ramrod straight. The two men, both in white robes, then sat on twin 
thrones. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second millennium of Christian history began with a  
painful wound for the unity of the church,'' the patriarch said, 
referring to the Great Schism of 1054 when the Eastern church 
definitively split from Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is ending now with a positive sign ... a sincere effort by  
Christian churches to heal that wound,'' added the 84-year-old 
patriarch. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul, who has made reconciliation a principal goal of the  
Vatican's millennium celebrations, said he was encouraging efforts 
for greater cooperation ``among all those who call themselves 
Christians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he also raised the issue of the persecution of Catholics  
under the various communist regimes that took power in Europe after 
World War II. It is particularly sensitive in Romania, where 2,400 
churches and other property were seized from Eastern rite Catholics 
and given to the Orthodox. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastern rite Catholics follow an Orthodox-style liturgy but are  
loyal to the pope. 
</P>
<P>
	The patriarch was accused of collaboration with communist leader  
Nicolae Ceausescu's government. He resigned after the regime was 
overthrown in 1989 and entered a monastery. Three months later, 
church leaders pressed him to return. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope my visit helps heal the wounds'' from that period, the  
pope said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orthodox Church had been slow in issuing an invitation to  
the pope, in part due to the property disputes with Romania's 
Catholics. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the two churches agreed to a truce, although  
the pope was not allowed to travel to regions where Catholics 
dominate. Orthodox feared their authority might be undercut, and 
ethnic and religious passions stirred up. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, several hundred thousand Catholics traveled to the  
Romanian capital on special trains and buses. The crowds warmly 
applauded the pope. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a step towards unity, because at the beginning there was  
a single church,'' said 14-year-old student Flavia Haradgea. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a papal spokesman said early today that John Paul  
will meet moderate ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova either 
Monday or Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 07:04:20 </DATE_TIME>
