<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Mistakes Embassy for Depot  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO pledged to pursue its bombing  
campaign in the Balkans, but expressed regret today for a mistaken 
attack on the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. NATO's military 
spokesman, German Gen. Walter Jertz said military planners had 
mistaken the building that housed the Chinese Embassy for the 
federal Directorate for Supply and Procurement, a military facility 
that coordinates Yugoslavia's weapons imports. Yugoslav media said 
three Chinese were killed in the bombing, lowering an earlier 
report of four dead. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Attack, US, Brit Embassies  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Demonstrators today hurled chunks of concrete at  
the U.S. and British embassies in the Chinese capital, protesting 
NATO's accidental bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. 
Windows at the American compound were broken, and at least four 
cars belonging to staff members were smashed. A group of protesters 
tried to ignite one car and then started shoving police who stopped 
them. Protests also were held in Shanghai, Guangzhou, and Hong 
Kong. The demonstrations in Guangzhou, a large city in southern 
China, involved tens of thousands of students from more than 10 
universities. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: China Bombing 'Tragic'  
</P>
<P>
	TINKER AIR FORCE BASE, Okla. (AP) -- Although he called the  
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade a tragic mistake, 
President Clinton said NATO has tried to minimize damage in its 
campaign against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces. 
NATO aircraft have made more than 10,000 bombing runs with 
relatively few casualties since airstrikes began March 24, he said. 
``We need some sense of proportion here,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Surveys Tornado Damage  
</P>
<P>
	DEL CITY, Okla. (AP) -- Following an aerial tour of the outskirts  
of Oklahoma City today, President Clinton said he's never seen so 
much destruction over such a wide area. The president promised up 
to $12.5 million to provide temporary jobs for victims of the 
deadly tornadoes that leveled entire neighborhoods and killed at 
least 50 people this past week in Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas and 
Tennessee. Half of the funds will immediately be made available to 
put 3,500 Oklahomans and 600 Kansans to work. Clinton also said he 
would ask Congress for an additional $372 million for FEMA's 
disaster relief fund. 

</P>
<P>
	Prom Goes On Despite Tornado  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Students were able to salvage their prom  
tonight even though many lost their homes and clothing to the 
deadly storms that swept through the state last week. Wearing 
outfits donated by local shops and rival Edmond North High School 
students, the Del City High School couples arrived at prom hoping 
to cap a week of bad memories with good ones. Junior Traci 
Harriman, 17, was wearing a black satin gown trimmed with silver 
sequins that she picked out from among the hundreds of dresses that 
were donated. ``My house is pretty much gone. I was so fortunate to 
have these girls help me, or I wouldn't have been able to go to my 
prom,'' she said. ``I think they are angels.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Belfast Accord 'In Crisis'  
</P>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams today  
demanded that his IRA-allied party be immediately included in a new 
Protestant-Catholic government, the intended centerpiece of the 
year-old Northern Ireland peace accord. Addressing more than 1,000 
supporters at his party's annual conference, Adams emphasized that 
the outlawed group won't be persuaded to start destroying its 
weapons stockpiles, a goal contained in the accord, ``no matter how 
this is presented.'' Protestant politician David Trimble, the 
designated leader of the future 12-member government, has demanded 
some IRA disarmament before his Ulster Unionist Party will accept 
two Sinn Fein politicians as government colleagues. 

</P>
<P>
	Chiasson Remembered at Funeral  
</P>
<P>
	PETERBOROUGH, Ontario (AP) -- Some of hockey's greatest names  
today celebrated the life of Carolina Hurricane's defenseman Steve 
Chiasson at an emotional funeral mass. Wayne Gretzky, NHL 
commissioner Gary Bettman, the Hurricanes and numerous hockey stars 
joined the Chiasson family and friends for a standing-room-only 
congregation at the 800-seat Cathedral of St. Peter's-in-Chains. 
Chaisson died in a single vehicle accident near his Raleigh, N.C., 
home Monday morning. 

</P>
<P>
	Phillies Beat Rockies 7-2  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Joel Bennett won his first major league start and  
Mike Lieberthal homered twice as the Philadelphia Phillies beat the 
Colorado Rockies 7-2 Saturday. Scott Rolen, Rico Brogna and Ron 
Gant also homered for the Phillies, who shut down the Rockies for 
the second straight day. After scoring 25 runs in the last two 
games of its road trip, Colorado has managed just three in two 
games against Philadelphia. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
</TEXT>
