<DOCNO> APW19990508.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 05:54:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rose Jr. Starting Over, Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Six months shy of his 30th birthday, Pete Rose  
Jr. is starting over on one of baseball's lowest rungs. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose Jr. is getting ready to return to the New Jersey Jackals,  
an independent league team he played for last summer while trying 
to hang onto his major league dreams. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of baseball's all-time hits leader got his spirits up  
when the Los Angeles Dodgers gave him a minor league contract and 
invited him to training camp this spring at his father's behest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers released him from their farm system during the last  
week of spring training, leaving Rose Jr. to return home and look 
for another chance somewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	He had to settle for the Jackals.  
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I have to go to the Northern League and put some  
numbers up,'' Rose Jr. said in a telephone interview Friday 
evening. ``Now I'm looking for the opportunity to get my foot back 
in the door. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nothing special, nothing to brag about, but it's  
baseball. I want the scouts to come and see me and say 1997 wasn't 
a fluke. Everyone has a fit somewhere. I've just got to go find 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rose Jr. has spent most of his professional career trying vainly  
to find that fit since Baltimore drafted him in the 13th round in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The stocky infielder with his father's looks joined his father's  
organization and realized his dream of playing for the Cincinnati 
Reds in 1997. He hit .308 at Double-A with 25 homers and was called 
up on Sept. 1, when he started at first base and got a single with 
his father looking on. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been downhill from there. He didn't start again and went  
2-for-14 overall with nine strikeouts, then got into a contract 
dispute and wound up at Triple-A the next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Passed over by younger prospects, Rose Jr. chose free agency  
rather than accept a demotion to Double-A. He latched on with 
Pittsburgh's Triple-A team in Nashville, hit .208 and was released 
a month later. He finished the season playing left field for the 
Jackals and hitting .424 in a dozen games. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Dodgers invited him to training camp and gave him  
uniform No. 74, he considered it a turning point. He went 0-for-8 
in exhibition games with one RBI before being assigned to the minor 
league camp and then released. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very tough,'' Rose Jr. said. ``When something burns so  
much inside of you, it just drives you crazy and you find yourself 
in tears and shaking your head. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the first time that has ever happened to me. I've just  
got to keep moving on. It's just another setback. Lord knows I've 
had setbacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While his agent tried to find him a spot in some team's farm  
system, Rose Jr. worked out in his hometown for the last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what he's been doing, Rose Jr. said, ``Besides driving  
everybody around me crazy and wanting to throw the remote through 
the TV every time I see a baseball game? 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been swinging and throwing and just waiting.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 05:54:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army Grounds Hueys After crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army grounded its fleet of aging UH-1 Huey  
helicopters Friday because of concern that the recent crash of an 
air ambulance may signal a structural problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Four crew members were injured, two critically, when the  
helicopter from Fort Rucker, Ala., crashed May 1. The helicopter 
was returning to the base after transporting a burn victim to a 
hospital in Birmingham when it lost part of the tail boom in 
flight, the Army said. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from the Army headquarters at the Pentagon said  
metal fatigue in the helicopter's tail fin is suspected. During the 
indefinite grounding, the Army and its reserve units plan to 
inspect each of the approximately 1,000 UH-1s for similar problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``This action was taken as a precaution to ensure the safety of  
soldiers,'' a statement from the Army said. 
</P>
<P>
	The UH-1, made by Bell Helicopter Textron, became a military  
mainstay, ferrying Americans troops in and out of battle during the 
Vietnam War. The $4.7 million aircraft is about 57 feet long, has a 
48-foot rotor and can reach speeds of up to 139 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	In March last year, the Army and National Guard grounded their  
fleets after pilots complained the engines surged unpredictably. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army had already placed wide restrictions on the Hueys,  
including barring flights in clouds and over water. The Army 
studied the engine surge problem but did not find a cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 14:49:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Female Graduates From Citadel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- The Citadel on Saturday graduated its  
first female cadet, ending a male-only tradition at the military 
school that stretched more than 150 years before ending as a result 
of a federal court fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Ruth Mace, a magna cum laude graduate in business  
administration, received her degree from her father, Emory Mace, 
the school's commandant of cadets. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news conference after the ceremony, she told reporters she  
does not regard herself ``as a pioneer'' in ending single-gender 
education at The Citadel. 
</P>
<P>
	Mace was clearly the best-known of the 386 cadets to graduate  
during ceremonies that featured Republican presidential hopeful Pat 
Buchanan warning about declining American military power. 
</P>
<P>
	She was greeted with applause as she accepted the degree. There  
had been some hissing during a ceremony earlier in the school year 
when she received her senior class ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Citadel officials nor Buchanan mentioned Mace or the  
school's controversial all-male admission's policy during the 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	Mace entered The Citadel in 1996 after the school dropped its  
all-male admissions policy. That change came after the U.S. Supreme 
Court struck down a similar policy at Virginia Military Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	The Citadel had fought a three-year battle started by Shannon  
Faulkner, who sought to join the corps of cadets. Faulkner was 
admitted in 1995 under a judge's order, but quit in less than a 
week, citing stress and isolation. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other women entered with Mace. Kim Messer and Jeanie  
Mentavlos quit after the first semester, saying they had been hazed 
and harassed. Both women sued the school, Messer's lawsuit has been 
settled, Mentavlos' case is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth woman, Petra Lovetinska, next year is expected to  
become The Citadel's first four-year graduate. Mace graduated in 
three years by transferring credits from a community college. 
</P>
<P>
	The Citadel now has 42 female cadets among its 1,800 students.  
</P>
<P>
	Mace will be an analyst with a business consulting firm in  
Charlotte, N.C., but noted she's only 21 and ``I don't know what I 
want to do with the rest of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mace also announced she became engaged Friday night. She did not  
identify her fiance, except to say he was a senior who also 
graduated Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
