<HEADLINE> Star Wars Star's Kids To Miss Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Their dad may star in this year's most  
anticipated film, but Liam Neeson's children won't get tickets to 
see ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The movie is too dense for younger kids. There's too much  
going on,'' Neeson said in Friday's Daily News. The film opens May 
19. 
</P>
<P>
	When the actor told his 4-year-old son Michael that he was going  
to a ``Star Wars'' party, Neeson said he had to assure his son 
``that the movie is only pretend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neeson also said playing the Jedi Master Qui-Gon Jinn was a  
challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're playing a mythological character,'' he said. ``He's 300  
stories all around the world of a particular type. The key is to 
play the type that people will recognize and make it individual.'' 
</P>
