<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dairy Farmers Seek Price Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dairy farmers, hoping to make it through a  
disastrous agricultural year, are backing several measures intended 
to shield the industry from the wild price swings that have 
devastated other farm sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Milk marketing order reform, dairy compacts and price supports  
are major buzz words for the industry, which is trying to learn 
from the harsh experiences of grain and livestock farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Those sectors were hit hard by plummeting prices in the last  
year, and analysts have said the farm industry won't see much of a 
rebound this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to be the next train wreck in agriculture,''  
said Christopher Galen, spokesman for the National Milk Producers 
Federation. ``A lot of those policy initiatives are aimed at 
stemming the train away from the bridge that's out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the policies have elicited something of a turf war with  
regions battling each other as well as farmers sparring with the 
processing industry. Many lawmakers have joined in the dairy fight 
to protect their regions. 
</P>
<P>
	``This fight pits David against Goliath, with our family farmers  
up against a powerful lobby,'' said Sen. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt. 
``Maintaining fair pricing policy benefits family farmers and 
consumers. This is an uphill battle we must win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., ``Our dated and pointless  
interference by the federal government in dairy policy has cost us 
too many Wisconsin farms. My legislative goal is to finally stop 
the perversion of dairy markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The milk marketing order reform proposal basically would  
overhaul the federal milk pricing system, which is divided 
regionally into what are known as orders that help set the price 
processors pay dairy farmers, much like the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	The price is higher the farther a farm is from Eau Claire, Wis.,  
which was considered the hub of dairy production when the system 
was established decades ago as a way to ensure all regions had 
sufficient milk supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	But milk marketing orders and a reform proposal by Agriculture  
Secretary Dan Glickman have sparked fierce debate among farmers, 
particularly those in the Midwest who have traditionally gotten 
lower prices. Glickman's proposal seeks to slightly close that 
disparity for the Midwest, much to the chagrin of farmers in other 
parts of the country. Several lawmakers have proposed legislation 
to overturn Glickman's proposed regulation, which is set to go 
before producers in a referendum in August. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a middle ground between the archaic status quo and a  
complete elimination of the market order system,'' insisted Rep. 
Ron Kind, D-Wis. ``If the dairy industry is to remain competitive, 
Congress should not advocate a rigid regulatory pricing system that 
pits region-against-region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of dairy compacts is just as contentious, with  
lawmakers from the Northeast and South uniting against the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	In the regional dairy compacts, states band together to set what  
they consider a ``fair price'' for fluid milk, which is higher than 
the federal government's minimum. A compact operating in the 
Northeast, covering Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New 
Hampshire, Rhode Island and Vermont, expires Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast region wants Congress to extend its compact while  
lawmakers from the South are pushing for their own. Opponents say 
the compacts will encourage overproduction and depress milk prices 
in other parts of the country. Supporters say they shield producers 
from fluctuating prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, compact supporters have 39 cosponsors in the Senate and  
more than 150 in the House, but with lawmakers from the Midwest 
staunchly opposed, industry observers can expect a fierce battle as 
the issue moves through Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation for price supports is the least controversial.  
</P>
<P>
	Under the price support program, which is due to expire Dec. 31,  
the government buys butter, cheese, nonfat dry milk or skim milk 
powder whenever the market price drops below a government-set 
level. The result is a boost in prices so dairy farmers are 
protected from extremely low levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our contention is that is a fairly cost effective way of  
providing a safety net in agriculture,'' said Galen, of the milk 
producers federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
