<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	US Consulate Attacked in China  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Protesters broke into and severely burned a U.S.  
consulate building in southwest China in the worst attack yet in 
two days of protests outside U.S. buildings across China, a U.S. 
Embassy spokesman said Sunday. A large number of people broke into 
the consulate compound in Chengdu and severely burned the consulate 
general's residence, said Tom Cooney, an embassy spokesman in 
Beijing. No U.S. staff were injured and Chinese police used tear 
gas to disperse the crowd, he said. In Bejing, more than 1,000 
protesters hurled rocks and lumps of concrete at embassy buildings 
and cars in Beijing. Demonstrators also protested outside the 
British Embassy. 

</P>
<P>
	Bombing of Chinese Embassy A Mistake  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO military planners mistakenly  
thought the Chinese embassy in Belgrade that was accidentally 
bombed was a weapons depot, officials said Saturday night. NATO 
pledged to pursue its bombing campaign in the Balkans, but did 
express regret for the mistaken attack Yugoslav media said three 
Chinese were killed in the bombing, lowering an earlier report of 
four dead. 

</P>
<P>
	Belfast Accord 'In Crisis'  
</P>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams demanded  
that his IRA-allied party be immediately included in a new 
Protestant-Catholic government, the intended centerpiece of the 
year-old Northern Ireland peace accord. Addressing more than 1,000 
supporters at his party's annual conference Saturday, Adams 
emphasized that the outlawed group won't be persuaded to start 
destroying its weapons stockpiles, a goal contained in the accord, 
``no matter how this is presented.'' Protestant politician David 
Trimble, the designated leader of the future 12-member government, 
has demanded some IRA disarmament before his Ulster Unionist Party 
will accept two Sinn Fein politicians as government colleagues. 

</P>
<P>
	TWA Flight May Have Been Held  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms  
had concluded within six months after TWA Flight 800 crashed off 
the coast of Long Island that mechanical failure was to blame, but 
the FBI sat on the report, The Washington Post is reporting in 
Sunday editions. The paper says that FBI officials, still convinced 
terrorists had downed the plane, dismissed the 24-page ATF report, 
prepared in January 1997, as ``unprofessional and reprehensible'' 
and even persuaded a Treasury Department undersecretary to help 
them suppress it. The Post said it was November 1997 before the FBI 
acknowledged publicly that a mechanical flaw had ignited the Boeing 
747's central fuel tank, causing the crash. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Surveys Tornado Damage  
</P>
<P>
	DEL CITY, Okla. (AP) -- Following an aerial tour of the outskirts  
of Oklahoma City Saturday, President Clinton said he's never seen 
so much destruction over such a wide area. The president promised 
up to $12.5 million to provide temporary jobs for victims of the 
deadly tornadoes that leveled entire neighborhoods and killed at 
least 50 people this past week in Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas and 
Tennessee. Half of the funds will immediately be made available to 
put 3,500 Oklahomans and 600 Kansans to work. Clinton also said he 
would ask Congress for an additional $372 million for FEMA's 
disaster relief fund. 

</P>
<P>
	Prom Goes On Despite Tornado  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Students were able to salvage their prom  
Saturday night even though many lost their homes and clothing to 
the deadly storms that swept through the state last week. Wea ring 
outfits donated by local shops and rival Edmond North High School 
students, the Del City High School couples arrived at prom hoping 
to cap a week of bad memories with good ones. 

</P>
<P>
	Stars Beat Blues in OT  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Joe Nieuwendyk's goal with 11:38 left in overtime  
gave the Dallas Stars a 5-4 victory over the St. Louis Blues 
Saturday night and a 2-0 lead in their Western Conference semifinal 
series. The teams will meet at St. Louis Monday night in the third 
game of the best-of-7 series. Nieuwendyk took a perfect pass from 
Sergei Zubov as both teams played a man short in a four-on-four 
situation and whipped a shot from just inside the right circle past 
the glove of goaltender Grant Fuhr. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Trounce Padres 11-1  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Tom Glavine earned a measure of revenge against  
San Diego, the team that beat him twice in the NL championship 
series, and Ryan Klesko drove in three runs on three extra-base 
hits as the Atlanta Braves routed the Padres 11-1 Saturday night. 
Glavine (2-3) allowed five hits in seven innings to win his second 
straight decision and had two RBI singles. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
