<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9:20 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Protesters Attack U.S. Embassy  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- More than a thousand demonstrators attacked the  
U.S. Embassy in Beijing with rocks, smashed up embassy cars and 
scuffled with hundreds of police officers today in a protest over 
the accidental NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. 
Police pushed back demonstrators who tried to ram a van and hurl a 
burning American flag through the embassy gate. Protesters used 
pieces of concrete that had been left in piles by workers 
rebuilding sidewalks to break many of the windows in embassy 
buildings spread over one block. Several cars were smashed with 
chunks of concrete. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Concerned by Embassy Missile  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council today expressed shock  
and concern over the NATO missile strike on China's embassy in 
Belgrade which reportedly killed three people. While apologizing 
for the loss of life, the United States and its NATO allies 
countered that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic bore the blame 
for any casualties from the NATO raids because he had refused to 
comply with international demands for a peaceful settlement in 
Kosovo. ``NATO would never target civilians and NATO would never 
target an embassy,'' Deputy U.S. Ambassador Peter Burleigh told the 
council. China's state-run news agency Xinhua said three people 
died. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Gun Groups May Back Clinton Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two firearms industry groups have agreed to  
support some of the Clinton administration's new gun-control 
proposals, including raising the age eligibility for buying a 
handgun from 18 to 21 and holding parents criminally responsible 
for allowing children access to guns, The Washington Post reported 
today. Leaders of the American Shooting Sports Council and the 
National Shooting Sports Council also agreed on measures forbidding 
juveniles convicted of violent felonies from ever buying a gun and 
requiring people who sell guns at gun shows to make background 
checks on the buyers, the newspaper reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Jones Lawyers Seek Nearly $500,000  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Lawyers for Paula Jones say they want  
President Clinton to pay nearly $500,000 to cover their costs 
following a judge's finding that Clinton had committed civil 
contempt in the sexual harassment case. Clinton's lawyer called the 
request unreasonable. The president already paid $850,000 to settle 
the case while its dismissal was on appeal. The compensation 
proposal yesterday came a month after U.S. District Judge Susan 
Webber Wright found Clinton in contempt for giving intentional, 
false testimony about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. 

</P>
<P>
	Key Pakistani Publisher Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- In the latest attack on journalists in  
Pakistan, a dozen police stormed the home of a magazine owner today 
and arrested him, witnesses said. Police broke down the outside 
gate of Najam Sethi's home in the Punjab provincial capital of 
Lahore, his wife Jugnoo Mohsin said. Sethi owns a weekly 
English-language news magazine, The Friday Times. The newspaper has 
been critical of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's government and Sethi 
has issued public statements saying he feared being arrested. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Unveils Saddam Inspired Resort  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq has added a new city to its map -- a  
lakeside vacation complex where nearly every brick is engraved with 
President Saddam Hussein's initials. The Iraqi leader has been 
awarded a key to the city of Saddamiat al-Tharthar, 85 miles west 
of Baghdad. Sprawled along an artificial lake, the complex was 
built in the past 11 months without the knowledge of most Iraqis, 
who only learned of its existence when the award ceremony was 
broadcast on state television. 

</P>
<P>
	Penguins Beat Maple Leafs 2-0  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Dan Kesa scored a power-play goal in the first  
period and Tom Barrasso needed to make only 20 saves as the 
Pittsburgh Penguins won their second-round playoff opener against 
the Toronto Maple Leafs, 2-0 last night. Game 2 in the best-of-7 
Eastern Conference semifinal is tomorrow night. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Cowboys Coach Hospitalized  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Former Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry is  
undergoing treatment for leukemia in a local hospital, according to 
his son, Tom Jr., The Dallas Morning News reported today. Landry, 
74, entered the hospital Tuesday and is expected to remain under 
the care of physicians for the next 30 days. ``Fortunately, this 
was diagnosed at an early stage and treatment was begun 
immediately,'' the younger Landry said. ``The family and doctors 
are optimistic that they will be successful in their efforts.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
