<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Relief Efforts Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOORE, Okla. (AP) -- Hundreds of relief workers on Saturday  
labored under a searing sun to sort through truckloads of donated 
goods waiting for delivery to the thousands left homeless by last 
week's devastating tornadoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Whitaker, one of nine pastors at the First Baptist Church,  
said almost all 200,000 square feet at the church have been put to 
use in the relief effort. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Red Cross, the Salvation Army, the Federal  
Emergency Management Agency and others have established operations 
inside while a cafeteria feeds three meals a day to about 3,000 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	It was by happenstance that the church became a shelter,  
Whitaker said. The church stands just across the street from where 
major damage occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``All people could see after the tornado passed was the light of  
our cross and they started coming this way,'' Whitaker said. ``From 
the moment the tornado happened, the church became the primary hub 
for this area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Storms killed at least 50 people in Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas and  
Tennessee and injured hundreds more. More than 9,000 homes were 
destroyed in the greater Oklahoma City area and more than 8,500 
buildings in Kansas were severely damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Johns, president of the Southwestern Insurance Information  
Service, said damage estimates continue to increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on the number of claims received so far, this could be a  
statewide insured loss of $750 million with about $600-plus million 
in the Oklahoma City metro area,'' Johns said. ``By comparison, the 
worst tornado in the country was in 1975 in Nebraska with insured 
total loss of $1.1 billion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Polley and Tony Gray left their jobs at a manufacturing  
plant in Pella, Iowa, on Thursday and drove to Oklahoma to pitch in 
with the relief effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a family of my own and what goes around comes around,''  
Polley said. ``If we ever get in a time of need in Iowa, I hope 
someone helps us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of relief service vans and trucks were in a large parking  
lot on the east side of the church. Six refrigerated trucks sat in 
back, loaded with meat, fresh produce, milk and other perishables. 
</P>
<P>
	Beverly Binkowski of the Red Cross said 24 trucks have been sent  
out to deliver meals in the field and the agency has delivered 
10,000 meals since the tornadoes struck. 
</P>
<P>
	A half-dozen insurance companies set up emergency operations out  
of vans in the same lot as did several phone companies, which made 
dozens of lines available for victims to call loved ones, insurance 
companies and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheryl Maxfield, a Blair High School sophomore, willingly gave  
up her Saturday to join the relief effort after seeing all of the 
damage on television. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of scary to see,'' she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
