<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *James E. Charlet    	
</P>
<P>
	CLARKSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- James E. Charlet, the former publisher  
and general manager of The Leaf-Chronicle, died Thursday at 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlet purchased a share in The Leaf-Chronicle in 1946 and went  
on to build a chain of 14 newspapers. By 1960, the firm owned the 
largest group of weeklies published in a single plant in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	Publications included the Stewart County Times, Donelson News  
Diary, Suburban News, Madison Community News, Goodlettsville 
Gazette, Hendersonville Star-News, Dickson County Herald, 
Springfield Herald, the Gallatin Examiner, Ashland City Times and 
Waverly News Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlet, his wife and three other stockholders sold The  
Leaf-Chronicle in 1973 to Multimedia but Charlet continued as 
president and publisher until 1978, turning the newspaper over to 
his son, James E. Charlet Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a son, daughter, five grandchildren and seven  
great-grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Leon Hess    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leon Hess, an oil tycoon and the owner of the  
New York Jets, who last year came close to seeing his team return 
to the Super Bowl one last time, died Friday from complications of 
a blood disease. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess, one of the wealthiest owners in professional sports, was  
in a group that bought the Jets of the American Football League in 
1963, when they were the New York Titans. He bought out his 
partners in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess died without seeing the Jets back in the Super Bowl. Their  
only appearance came in 1969 when Joe Namath led them to a landmark 
victory over the Baltimore Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess was known as a generous owner who promoted a family  
atmosphere for his team. When Dennis Byrd was temporarily paralyzed 
in a collision with a teammate during a 1992 game, Hess offered 
financial and medical support throughout Byrd's recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess acquired Amerada in 1969 after an ownership battle with  
Phillips Petroleum. Forbes magazine last year listed his net worth 
at $720 million. He stepped down as chairman and CEO of Amerada 
Hess Corp. in 1995. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Tibor Kalman    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tibor Kalman, an innovative graphic designer who  
used visual images to try to effect social change, died Sunday of 
non-Hodgkins lymphoma. He was 49. 
</P>
<P>
	He died in a hotel near San Juan, Puerto Rico.  
</P>
<P>
	Kalman, who founded and ran the Manhattan design firm M&AMP;Co, had  
his staff do work that evoked the look of handmade signs, menus and 
flyers instead of a more polished corporate style. 
</P>
<P>
	He designed Barnes &AMP; Noble's distinctive shopping bag early in  
his career, and later did an album cover for the Talking Heads. 
Kalman produced a photographic series about New Yorkers' 
interactions with Times Square, which hung on a building there. 
</P>
<P>
	Kalman also worked as an editor and creative director at the  
magazines Art Forum and Interview. He was editor-in-chief of 
Colors, a magazine published by the clothing company Benetton. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Paul Liacos    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Retired Supreme Judicial Court Chief Justice Paul  
Liacos, whose tenure was marked by decisions on large issues such 
as abortion, racial bias and the right to an education, died 
Thursday at age 69. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not released.  
</P>
<P>
	Liacos, who gained a reputation as an unabashed liberal, was  
appointed chief justice in 1989 by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis after 
serving 13 years as an associate justice. He stepped down in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenure, the SJC held that the state constitution  
prohibited the death penalty, the court provided broader protection 
for a woman's access to abortion, and it gave defendants greater 
protection in search and seizure cases. 
</P>
<P>
	In a major opinion written by Liacos, the court found that the  
state constitution requires children be provided an adequate 
education, a decision that spurred enactment of the state's 
ambitious education reform law. Liacos also opposed minimum 
mandatory prison sentences, contending that sentencing should be 
left to the discretion of judges. 
</P>
<P>
	Liacos founded the SJC's Committee to Study Racial and Ethnic  
Bias in the Courts and served as chairman of the national 
Conference of Chief Justices' Committee on Discrimination in the 
Courts. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Jesus Montane    	
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Jesus Montane, one of an old band of  
revolutionaries who fought alongside Fidel Castro to seize power in 
Cuba in the 1950s, died Friday of a heart attack. His age was not 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Dictator Fulgencio Batista jailed Montane with Castro and other  
guerrillas in Cuba's Isle of Pines for several years after they 
mounted a failed attack in 1953 on the Moncada army barracks in 
Santiago, launching the revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	The revolutionaries were later released under an amnesty decree  
and fled to Mexico, where they planned a second attack on Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	They returned in 1956, vanished into the countryside and  
continued fighting Batista, finally overthrowing him Jan. 1, 1959. 

</P>
<P>
                           *William Owens    	
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- William Owens, a grade school dropout who  
played for a dozen teams in the Negro leagues in the 1920s and 
'30s, died Wednesday of complications from diabetes. He was 98. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens, who had only a sixth-grade education, broke in with the  
Washington Potomacs in 1923. He played briefly with the 
Indianapolis ABCs and spent the next decade barnstorming with many 
teams before ending his career with the Detroit Stars in 1933. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Eugene Schroeder    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Eugene Schroeder, a reporter with The Associated  
Press for more than 40 years, died Wednesday from complications 
following a stroke. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to joining the AP in Detroit in 1958, Schroeder was a  
correspondent with International News Service, a forerunner of UPI, 
on roving assignments that included the fight for civil rights in 
the South. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder was AP's Lansing, Mich., correspondent in the early  
1960s. He chronicled Michigan's successful effort to adopt the 
nation's first new state constitution since 1909. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder later was a member of an AP task force on racial  
issues, joined the AP newsfeatures staff in New York in 1978, and 
was a special features editor when he suffered an incapacitating 
stroke last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a cousin.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Darwyn Swalve    	
</P>
<P>
	RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) -- Darwyn Swalve, a 6-foot-9 actor who  
used his bulk to advantage in a succession of television and movie 
bad-guy roles, died Wednesday of a heart attack, The 
Press-Enterprise reported. He was 53. 
</P>
<P>
	He had recently completed a role in Nickelodeon's ``The Journey  
of Allen Strange'' series, scheduled to air this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Swalve weighed 300-plus pounds and was a onetime  
semi-professional football player, but was known as a gentle man 
who disliked violence. 
</P>
<P>
	He began acting after he was discharged from the Marine Corps in  
1968. He appeared with Southern California theater companies and 
worked as a stuntman before making his film debut in 1983 in ``The 
Zoo Gang,'' which starred Ben Vereen. 
</P>
<P>
	Swalve's other films included ``City Heat,'' ``Heartbreak  
Ridge,'' ``Barton Fink,'' ``Hands of Steel,'' ``Police Academy 6,'' 
``Open House'' and ``Underground.'' Television credits included 
``The A-Team,'' ``Jake and the Fatman'' and ``Moonlighting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
