<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Search Goes On for Tornado Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- They are the missing: Tram Bui, a  
23-year-old Seminole woman who was blown from underneath a highway 
overpass, and Barbara and John Potton, a British couple who 
vanished while traveling in a motor home north of Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	The list of those still unaccounted-for after Monday's fierce  
tornadoes that killed 46 people in Oklahoma and Kansas has been 
narrowed to three. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pottons, in their 60s, haven't been heard from since calling  
relatives a few hours before the tornadoes struck, Ray Blakeney of 
the state medical examiner's office said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason we're concerned about them is they always contact  
their family every day that they are traveling,'' he said. He 
didn't know their hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	Bui was last seen trying to shelter herself from the storm  
beneath an Interstate 35 overpass. Police Sgt. Nate Tarver said the 
fate of all three may never be known. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know what a tornado does with people,'' he said.  
``Some people are picked up and dropped with no injuries. And 
others are never seen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deadly weather didn't stop in the central Plains -- on  
Tuesday and Wednesday, storms killed four people in Tennessee and 
another person in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers planned to search the rubble again today. More than  
10,500 homes are estimated to have been destroyed or damaged in 
Oklahoma. In Kansas, 1,500 buildings were destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	The winds that demolished those structures reached 318 mph, some  
of the most intense ever recorded, said Joshua Wurman, assistant 
professor of meteorology at the University of Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a pretty reliable estimate,'' Wurman said of his  
preliminary radar data. ``It's possible we'll go through every scan 
we have and find higher wind speeds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The previous highest speed recorded by Wurman was 286 mph in an  
Oklahoma tornado in 1991. Wurman gathers his data with radar units 
mounted on trucks, a program called Doppler on Wheels funded by the 
National Science Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, who planned to visit Oklahoma today, added  
five counties to the state's disaster declaration, bringing to 16 
the number of counties qualifying for assistance, Gov. Frank 
Keating said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma City police allowed people to bring in bulldozers and  
heavy equipment Friday to clear areas that had previously been 
restricted. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the state Board of Education decided to cancel the  
rest of the school year for students of Mulhall-Orlando Elementary 
School, which was destroyed by a tornado. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patching together something for 11 days would not be  
beneficial to the students and the time would be better spent 
building towards next school year,'' said Dennis Smith, 
superintendent of the school district 40 miles north of Oklahoma 
City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
