<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona Options Anderson to Tucson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Left-hander Brian Anderson, the odd man out in  
the Arizona Diamondbacks remodeled pitching rotation, was optioned 
to Triple-A Tucson on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks made room for right-handed reliever Amaury  
Telemaco, who started the season on the disabled list with 
tendinitis in his right shoulder. Telemaco's 30-day rehabilitation 
assignment in Tucson expired on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Buck Showalter emphasized that Anderson's assignment was  
temporary. He will get three starts, beginning Monday at Iowa, then 
rejoin the Diamondbacks around May 21 during their four-game series 
in Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's for Brian's benefit and our benefit,'' Showalter said.  
``We put a finite date on it. He'll be right back where he was. 
He'll be back with us in Colorado, maybe before that if somebody 
gets injured.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, 27, was diplomatic about the move.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's an unusual situation,'' he said. ``As much as I'd like to  
not believe it, it's strange because I almost saw it coming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There had been widespread speculation that Anderson would be  
traded after the Diamondbacks signed free-agent starters Randy 
Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre and Armando Reynoso in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Diamondbacks decided to keep Anderson, at least for now,  
using him as a reliever and as a possible starter if one of the 
five in the rotation was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson obviously was frustrated in the role and he struggled  
in his few relief appearances. He appeared in eight games, pitching 
a total of 10 1-3 innings, with an 0-1 record and a 9.58 ERA. 
Opponents were batting .364 against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter, who said he had ``a tough conversation'' with  
Anderson to tell him about the move, indicated the Diamondbacks 
likely would have sent Anderson to the minors for more work even if 
they had not activated Telemaco. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something Brian's in need of, just some time to get his  
confidence and get back the location on his fastball and 
curveball,'' Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who spent the two previous seasons with Cleveland, was  
Arizona's first pick in last year's expansion draft. He was 12-13 
for Arizona last season with a 4.33 ERA. He led the NL in fewest 
walks per nine innings at 1.0 but also tied for the lead in home 
runs allowed with 39. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking at it through their eyes,'' Anderson said. ``I'm  
not in the role I used to be in. I'm just insurance to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and Vladimir Nunez were the only Arizona pitchers who  
had a Triple-A option remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Telemaco was Arizona's fifth starter the last half of the 1998  
season. He was 6-9 with a 3.94 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``He pitched some good innings for us last year,'' Showalter  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Telemaco, 25, threw three innings Thursday night in Tucson,  
allowing one hit and a walk and striking out two. 
</P>
</TEXT>
