<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sautin Wins 3M Springboard Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Six months on his back is not the  
best position for an Olympic gold medal diver. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first competition since November when he underwent a  
surgical procedure to lance an infection on his back, Russia's 
premier diver, Dmitry Sautin, dominated an array of Olympic 
hopefuls by taking the gold on the 3-meter springboard at the 
International Swimming Hall of Fame Aquatic Complex on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sautin, 25, the reigning world 3-meter and platform champion and  
the 1996 Olympic platform gold medalist, has won this event four 
years in a row and five of the last six. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the god of diving,'' bronze medalist P.J. Bogart said.  
``I finally came into a meet relaxed. They've (Russians and 
Chinese) overlapped us but we're finally catching up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sautin scored 702.63 points in beating China's Xiong Ni (691.38)  
and Bogart (631.35). 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's platform final, Cai Yuyan of China defended her  
title by edging 15-year-old teammate Li Na. American teen Erica 
Sorgi, who finished behind 17-year-old Cai last year, botched her 
final two dives but held on for the bronze. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy we placed in the 3-meter and platform because it's a  
step in the right direction for the U.S., but I'm not happy with my 
diving today,'' Sorgi, 16, said. ``The whole Chinese team is 
outstanding but they train so many more hours than us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the synchronized competition, which is making its Olympic  
debut at Sydney in 2000, American brothers Justin and Troy Dumais 
captured their first gold medal as a diving duo in the 3-meter 
event. China's Xiong and Zhou Yilin were second and Americans 
Bogart and Chris Devine finished third. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dumais and Dumais, how much more synchro can you get than  
brothers?'' Justin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristin Link and Lindsay Long got silver in the women's  
synchronized platform event behind China's Cai and Li. Xiong 
received the only perfect 10 in Saturday finals on his fourth dive, 
a reverse 2 1/2 somersault. 
</P>
<P>
	Sautin, second behind Mark Ruiz heading into Sunday's platform  
finals, is also seeking his fourth straight gold atop the 10-meter 
board here. 
</P>
<P>
	He hadn't competed since August, but knew he would pick up where  
he left off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never doubted I'd dive again but I was a little scared when  
they cut it (infection) out,'' Sautin said. ``The time will come 
when the youngsters will do it, but not yet.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
