<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hunter's Foundation Holds Fundraiser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HERTFORD, N.C. (AP) -- The applause from the stands was polite  
and almost reverent Saturday when Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter walked 
toward the pitcher's mound with his family. 
</P>
<P>
	He sat in the middle of the baseball diamond at Perquimans  
County High School next to his wife as family, friends and former 
teammates held a ceremony to honor Hertford's favorite son and to 
kick off a foundation to aid those, like Hunter, suffering from Lou 
Gehrig's disease. 
</P>
<P>
	One girl read a poem about ``Jimmy,'' whom she thinks of as ``a  
hard worker to lend a hand, not a Hall of Famer.'' Then teammates 
spoke about the Hall of Fame pitcher's determination and courage as 
a player. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has more courage in his little finger than most people''  
have at all, former Oakland manager Alvin Dark said. 
</P>
<P>
	When it was finally his turn to speak, the five-time World  
Series winner could barely muster the words for the waiting, hushed 
crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	He thanked everyone for their help with the day's events to  
benefit the newly formed foundation. Hunter stepped away from the 
microphone, one hand lifted to wipe his face, and stepped back with 
a quip about the wind whistling into the mike. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this microphone would stop ringing, I could say  
something,'' he said to break the silent tension. ``I enjoyed this 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter, 53, was diagnosed in September with amyothropic lateral  
sclerosis, or ALS, a neurological disease that interferes with the 
signals the brain sends to the muscles. Over time, the muscles 
degenerate. The cause if unknown, and there's no cure. 
</P>
<P>
	It manifests itself differently. In Hunter's case, it affects  
his arms and hands, which means he can't raise them to shake hands 
or throw a baseball. His wife, Helen, helped him take off his navy 
New York Yankees cap before the Pledge of Allegiance. 
</P>
<P>
	About 5,000 people attended the kickoff for the Jim Catfish  
Hunter ALS Foundation, held along with a barbecue lunch, softball 
and baseball games and a silent auction. Items up for bid included 
balls signed by current Yankees Derek Jeter and Roger Clemens, 
black sequined boots worn by Dolly Parton, Yankees World Series 
paraphernalia and Vince Gill's guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	Former major leaguers on hand -- Oakland catcher Jim Pagliaroni,  
A's third baseman Sal Bando, Yankees first baseman Jim Spencer, 
Oakland outfielder Mike Hershberger, Hall of Fame pitcher Gaylord 
Perry, Yankees pitcher Ron Davis and pitcher Tommy John -- recalled 
Hunter as a friend. 
</P>
<P>
	A big gathering at the high school baseball field is nothing new  
this time of year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saturday before Mother's Day has been set aside for a local  
old-timers baseball game since Hunter started it in 1980, a year 
after he retired from the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the date coincided with the perfect game he pitched  
May 8, 1968, when he was with Oakland. It is one of only 13 perfect 
games in major league history. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter joked about Perry's fondness for food. Hunter and  
Pagliaroni, his catcher for the perfect game 31 years ago, 
reminisced. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike Hershberger, about the fifth or sixth inning ... walked  
by me and he says, `Hey, you walked a guy in the first inning.' ... 
And until the last out in the ball game I thought I had walked 
somebody. Until Sal Bando came up to me after the last out and said 
perfect game,'' Hunter said. 
</P>
<P>
	As amiable as ever, Hunter walked among the throngs of hometown  
friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to see it happen to him. That stuff he's got is bad.  
All we can do is hope and pray there's a cure,'' said Hertford 
resident Stanley ``Demp'' Pierce, 62. He remembers Hunter, or Jimmy 
as everyone here calls him, running around the ball park as a 
child. 
</P>
<P>
	Even during the autograph session, during which he stood and  
talked to those in line, he yelled out to his former teammates to 
sign faster because the line was getting long. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's his normal self,'' said Susan Harris, one of the day's  
organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always been a Catfish Hunter fan,'' said Keith Vaughan,  
the pastor of Hertford Baptist Church. ``Not many people get to 
meet (their) childhood hero.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now Vaughan helps support the family that has helped many in  
this small town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
