<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Guilty of Bus Stop Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANTON, Ga. (AP) -- Lawyers for a teen-ager convicted of fatally  
beating a younger boy vowed to appeal and argue that last month's 
massacre at a Colorado high school influenced the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Miller, 15, was convicted of felony murder by a jury  
Friday. Prosecutors said he beat 13-year-old Josh Belluardo Nov. 2 
at a school bus stop in their subdivision, and the younger boy died 
two days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller faces up to life in prison when he is sentenced.  
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney David Wolfe argued that his client never  
intended to kill Belluardo and should be convicted of involuntary 
manslaughter, not murder. 
</P>
<P>
	After the verdict, he said Judge C. Michael Roach's denial of  
motions to delay the trial because of the deadly shootings at 
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., would serve as the basis 
of an appeal. Two student gunmen killed 12 classmates and a teacher 
April 20 before taking their own lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a sad day that a case has to be tried involving  
the facts and circumstances that were involved in this case so soon 
after the tragedy in Littleton,'' Wolfe said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jonathan should be punished for his actions, but he shouldn't  
be punished for something that could never have been contemplated 
in his actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Garry Moss said he hoped the verdict would ``stop  
this insanity'' of children behaving violently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
