<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Cuban Spies Face Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The United States has added murder conspiracy  
charges against an alleged Cuban spy for the 1996 downing of two 
civilian airplanes flown by Cuban exiles searching for rafters in 
international waters. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten people had already been under indictment, charged with  
trying to penetrate U.S. military bases, infiltrate exile groups 
and manipulate U.S. media and political organizations. Authorities 
describe the spy ring as the largest Cuban espionage operation 
uncovered in the United States in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The new indictment returned Friday adds four new defendants and  
accuses Gerardo Hernandez of providing information about Brothers 
to the Rescue flights to Cuba before Cuban fighter jets shot down 
the Miami-based group's planes over international waters, killing 
four. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, who was arrested last year on spy-related charges by  
the FBI, ``received instructions that under no circumstances should 
Miami-based agents fly with (Brothers to the Rescue),'' the day the 
planes were shot down, the Justice Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very pleased to see that action is being taken against  
some of the participants,'' said Jose Basulto, the group's leader. 
``It was a case of premeditated murder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez alone was charged with conspiracy to perpetrate  
murder, which carries a maximum sentence of life in prison. After 
the planes were shot down, the indictment said, Cuba's spy agency 
recognized Hernandez for his role and promoted him to captain. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14 defendants also were accused of infiltrating, informing  
on and manipulating anti-Castro Cuban political groups in Miami and 
Dade County, spreading disinformation within the groups and 
carrying out orders from the Cuban government. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten defendants were arrested in September 1998 and remain in  
pretrial detention, prosecutors said. Five of them already have 
pleaded guilty to spy-related charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 14:14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bruins Coach Warns of 'Hate Factor' / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- There already was plenty of clean, hard hitting in  
Boston's opening-game playoff win over Buffalo. Imagine what will 
happen when the ``hate factor'' kicks in. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruins coach Pat Burns says that develops as a series goes on.  
And both sides expect the best-of-7 Eastern Conference semifinal, 
which resumes Sunday, to last a long time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not good enough to get cocky or to think this is going  
to be easy,'' Boston's Ray Bourque said Saturday. ``You're going to 
have to play through a lot of hits and a lot of physical stuff, but 
you're dishing it out as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's how we play. We're intense and the same thing for  
Buffalo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Peca, one of the NHL's top defensive forwards is a prime  
example of that with the Sabres. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is the hate factor. You're battling to get beyond the  
stage you're at with a team that's going to fight just as much,'' 
he said. ``You're going to exchange cheap shots. You're going to 
exchange words. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once the series is over you shake hands and appreciate the  
battle that was fought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston got the upper hand in that battle with a 4-2 win Thursday  
night. It scored three times against two-time defending NHL most 
valuable player Dominik Hasek, who played well, and added an 
empty-net goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you ever take the Dom factor away,'' Burns said.  
``He's a great goaltender.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, there is that other factor.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's too early in the series to really start hating each  
other,'' Burns said. ``As the playoff series goes on the hate 
factor comes into effect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe was even stingier than Hasek, a good  
sign for Boston in a series that figures to be low-scoring. He has 
a 1.71 goals against average in the playoffs, while his team has 
scored at least two goals in each of its seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our offense has been fine,'' said Boston's Jason Allison, who  
has at least one point in each playoff game. ``We don't score six 
or seven, but you don't usually need to in the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres need to score enough to avoid going down 2-0 for the  
15th time in a playoff series. They lost all 14 others. 
</P>
<P>
	They're expected to be without Miroslav Satan, who led them with  
40 goals but hasn't played since the third game of Buffalo's 
four-game sweep of Ottawa because of a foot injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've just got to come out and play with a little more  
desperation,'' defenseman Jason Woolley said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said it won't take much to put his  
team back in control -- just one win on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's how easy it switches,'' he said. ``We've got to adjust  
our game a little bit with the absence of Miro but there's no 
feeling that (the series) has gotten away from us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres had breakdowns in the neutral zone and around their  
net in the opener. They also failed to capitalize on some rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	But they put some solid hits on Bourque, one of the NHL's  
greatest players. Burns had no problem with it. That, he said, is 
the way the game should be played. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why do we get excited because Ray Bourque gets hit? `Oh,  
they're targeting Ray.' Of course, they're going to target Ray,'' 
Burns said. ``If the games are clean and the hits are clean, it's 
exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With two of the NHL's best goalies and two tight-checking teams,  
the emphasis is on defense. 
</P>
<P>
	That means knocking players off the puck, banging them into the  
boards and preparing to take return blows. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're meeting the same guy in the corner,'' Boston's Tim  
Taylor said. ``If he gets the puck out a couple of times, it really 
changes. You really want to go in there making sure you get that 
puck and create a battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the games go on, it'll create more of a rivalry.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
