<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:51:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL: VisionAire 500 is Non-Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indy Racing League will issue no points  
or official prize money to the teams and drivers who competed in 
the race where three spectators were killed by flying debris. 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Mehl, executive director of the IRL, said it will pay a  
specified amount to each owner and driver to help cover expenses 
incurred in the VisionAire 500 on May 1 at Lowe's Motor Speedway in 
Concord, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was called off after 79 of 208 laps. Wheel and  
suspension parts from a three-car wreck on lap 59 flew over catch 
fencing and into the grandstand. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the deaths, eight people were injured. A 9-year-old girl  
remained in critical condition Saturday at Carolinas Medical Center 
in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Each owner will receive an expense check of $17,500 per entry.  
In addition, the entry fee of $5,000 either will be refunded or 
canceled for each owner's entry. Each driver will receive an 
expense check for $2,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Under IRL rules, none of the race results count, so no winner is  
designated. 
</P>
<P>
	IRL and speedway officials are continuing their investigation of  
the accident and plan to reveal their findings next week. The 
speedway is refunding all ticket money or, upon fan request, 
donating the money to a trust fund established for the victims' 
families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
