<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Abreu Gets Good News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Philadelphia Phillies outfielder Bobby Abreu  
received encouraging news Saturday when doctors diagnosed him with 
a strained muscle in his right forearm. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury is expected to keep Abreu out of the lineup 5-7 days,  
but it could have been worse. The Phillies initially thought he 
might have an elbow injury that could have meant a trip to the 
disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is very good news,'' Philadelphia manager Terry Francona  
said. ``We'll sit him out (Sunday) and we'll let him hit early in 
St. Louis Monday and see how he feels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abreu said he initially felt soreness in his right throwing arm  
last week and the pain grew worse during batting practice Friday 
before Philadelphia's game against the Colorado Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Francona removed Abreu from the lineup 20 minutes before  
Friday's game and rested him again Saturday. The Phillies won both 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Abreu is hitting .348 with four homers, 17 RBIs and four stolen  
bases this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 07:23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Wins Women's 400M Hurdles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSAKA, Japan (AP) -- Romanian Lonela Tirlea outran Olympic  
champion Deon Hemmings of Jamaica and world record-holder Kim 
Batten of the United States in the women's 400-meter hurdles at the 
Japan Grand Prix on today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm more than happy,'' said Tirlea, who finished in 54.09  
seconds for one of two gold medals for Romania at the one-day event 
in western Japan. ``I ran pretty well while they were not at their 
best, I guess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hemmings finished second in 54.69, and Batten faded to finish  
third in 54.94, 2.33 seconds slower than her world record. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is my first race. It didn't go quite as well as I  
planned,'' said Batten. ``But I don't think this race is any 
indication of what I'm going to be like in July and in August.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five grand prix events will be held in Europe in July before  
August's world championships in Sevilla. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley Dorival won the men's 110-meter hurdles in a 1-2-3 finish  
by the United States. Dorival finished with a time of 13.36, 
followed by Allen Johnson's 13.38 and Mark Crear's 13.42. 
</P>
<P>
	``The season just started, and I'm satisfied with the result,''  
Dorival said. ``I now hope to perform as well in the U.S. national 
championships and the world championships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hungarian Balazs Koranyi surged ahead of four runners in the  
final lap to win the men's 800 meters in 1:47.70. David 
Krummenacker was second in 1:47.94, followed by fellow American 
Rich Kenah's 1:48.00. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt jet lag and woke up this morning at 5 a.m.,'' Koranyi  
said. ``Therefore I was not fresh, but turned out to be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's 800 meters, Diane Modahl of Britain overtook  
American Kathi Rounds in the final 15 meters and won the gold in 
2:03.83. Rounds finished second in 2:03.92 and Australia's Tamsyn 
Lewis was third at 2:04.17. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-day meet at Osaka's Nagai Stadium was the second of a  
series of 18 grand prix events this year, organized by the 
International Amateur Athletic Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	The first of the series was held in Rio de Janeiro on April 25,  
with the next and grand prix scheduled for Doha on May 13. The 
series culminates in the grand prix final in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
