<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 15:41:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reprieve Possible in Pizza Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A judge who thinks inmates unfairly spend  
too much time on death row has ordered a possible reprieve for a 
man who gunned down a pizza deliveryman. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Koskovich's death sentence would be commuted to life in  
prison if he is still alive five years from now, Judge Reginald 
Stanton ordered Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The process has become unacceptably cruel to defendants who  
spend long years under sentence of death while the judicial system 
conducts seemingly interminable proceedings which remind many 
observers of a cruelly whimsical cat toying with a mouse,'' Stanton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys say to their knowledge, such an order has  
never been issued at the trial court level. Prosecutors say Stanton 
exceeded his authority. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not aware of any judge ever having issued a sentence like  
this,'' said Alan Zegas, immediate past president of the 
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers of New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	He questioned whether a time limit on the death penalty was fair  
to the defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	``To place a time restriction upon its imposition can unfairly  
affect the rights of the defendant to appellate review,'' Zegas 
said. ``Almost every person who has been on death row has taken 
longer than 5 years to exhaust their appeals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Koskovich, 21, was sentenced to die Friday for killing pizza  
deliveryman Jeremy Giordano in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict and Stanton's condition are subject to automatic  
review, as are all death penalty sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	Former state Sen. John Russo, who sponsored the 1982 law that  
reinstated the death penalty in New Jersey, told The Star-Ledger of 
Newark for Saturday's editions that Stanton's ruling was 
``outrageous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He, in effect, has usurped the jury's function and reduced a  
death sentence to a life sentence -- and that's not his function,'' 
Russo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
