<DOCNO> APW19990508.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 22:12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Refugees Arrive in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Adem and Tanusha Raci scanned the group of  
Kosovo refugees who arrived Saturday at John F. Kennedy 
International Airport, craning for a glimpse of their daughter who 
was forced to flee her home. 
</P>
<P>
	Then they spotted her -- a crying 10-year-old Blrena Raci, who  
opened her arms for a hug from her parents. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a scene that played out over and over as 102 refugees --  
75 adults and 27 children -- escaping atrocities in the Yugoslavian 
province of Kosovo were reunited with family in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	They were the third group of ethnic Albanians to arrive this  
week. The United States has agreed to accept 20,000 refugees who 
have fled the Kosovo province to neighboring countries. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,000 refugees a week are expected to move through Fort  
Dix, N.J., and New York's Kennedy Airport to be housed temporarily 
at military bases or placed directly with sponsors or relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Sen. Chuck Schumer, D-N.Y., and other officials greeted the  
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are smiling on the outside because they are seeing their  
relatives. They are crying on the inside because they know what 
their homeland is going through,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Raci family, Blrena's arrival was bittersweet.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have waited so long for this,'' Raci said. He said he left  
his then-infant daughter in the care of her grandmother while he 
and his wife tried to carve out a new life in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl was separated from her grandmother when they fled  
Kosovo after their home was burned. She was living in a refugee 
camp in Macedonia for the past month. The grandmother, Raci 
believes, is in a refugee camp in Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	Two older sisters, one of whom Blrena had never before met,  
pressed four balloons and a bouquet of red roses into her hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the more than 200 people gathered at the airport had  
never before met their relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Nick Rugova, 31, of Bedford, N.Y., held up a sign bearing his  
cousin's name -- Nezir Rugova, who was separated from his wife and 
daughter when Serb troops herded them onto buses in Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has no idea where they are,'' Nick Rugova said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
