<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wind Affects Modesto Relays Sprints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MODESTO, Calif. (AP) -- Ato Boldon and Maurice Greene maintained  
their status as the world's top two 100-meter runners, but wind 
wiped out any chance of them bidding for a world record and earning 
a $200,000 bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon won his 100-meter heat in the revived Modesto Relays with  
a time of 9.89 seconds Saturday, and Greene won his heat in 9.91. 
Both times were wind-aided, however. 
</P>
<P>
	The cash bonus had been offered to any runner who broke the  
world record of 9.84 set by Canada's Donovan Bailey in the 1996 
Atlanta Olympics. But Boldon said he knew long before the race that 
the wind would wipe out any record time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so anal, and I knew four days ago we'd have a hard time,''  
he said after consulting an Internet weather service. ``I don't 
think anyone was thinking of the mark. Going into the blocks, I 
knew what it was like because of the wind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, his time of 9.89 seconds was excellent, especially for  
someone with a sore right hamstring that forced him to back off 
halfway through the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really didn't feel like I was pushing it at any point,''  
said Boldon, the world champion in the 200. ``I don't feel like I 
gave a great effort out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, the defending world champion in the 100, ran his time  
with a slightly milder tailwind, and Boldon said ``Maurice's race 
was faster, no question about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, the world's top-ranked sprinter last year, and Boldon  
both have clocked bests of 9.86 in the 100 under legal wind 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	In other events, Stacy Dragila tied her own American record in  
the women's pole vault by clearing 14 feet, 7 1/4 inches (4.45 
meters), matching the mark she set in the Modesto Relays in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Anjanette Kirkland tied the meet record of 12.70 in the women's  
100-meter hurdles, matching the time set by Jackie Joyner Kersee in 
1988. But Dan O'Brien, the defending Olympic champion and world 
record holder in the decathlon, finished only sixth in the men's 
100-meter hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	The Modesto Relays used to be one of the top meets on the  
American track and field schedule, attracting top sprinters such as 
Carl Lewis and Merlene Ottey in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	But in line with the sport's downward spiral in the United  
States throughout the 1990s, the meet lost fan and sponsor support 
in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, an infusion of cash from the Modesto-based Save Mart  
supermarket chain, which also is bidding to buy the Oakland 
Athletics, brought back some of the world's top sprinters as the 
Modesto Relays celebrated a 58th edition. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the $200,000 bonus for breaking the men's 100  
record, there was a $50,000 prize offered for a women's world 
record in the 100. Inger Miller won the women's 100 in 11.06, far 
off the world record of 10.49 set by Florence Griffith-Joyner in 
1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Apologizes for Embassy Strike  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO owned up to a ``tragic mistake''  
today -- the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade -- but 
expressed confidence that the error would not derail efforts to 
enroll Russian and Chinese support to end the Kosovo conflict. NATO 
issued a strong apology but made clear allied airstrikes will 
continue against Yugoslavia. In Beijing, a large crowd attacked the 
U.S. and British Embassies with chunks of concrete today, smashing 
windows and cars to protest the bombing. Protests also were held in 
Shanghai, Guangzhou and Hong Kong. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Leader Flies To Germany  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Kosovo's most prominent ethnic Albanian  
leader, Ibrahim Rugova, and Balkan envoys from Russia and the 
United Nations flew to Germany for talks today with Chancellor 
Gerhard Schroeder aimed at following up on a proposed peace plan 
for Kosovo. At the same time, German officials sought to limit 
damage to the diplomatic drive from the NATO bombing of the Chinese 
Embassy in Belgrade. 

</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Kosovars Reach Albania  
</P>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- Thousands of ethnic Albanians from  
villages in southwest Kosovo streamed into northern Albania today, 
describing an apparent new Serb campaign to force them out of the 
province. More than 5,000 refugees crossed the Albanian border by 
late afternoon, said officials of the Organization for Security and 
Cooperation in Europe. Refugees said Serb forces seized young men 
from their tractors as they headed toward the Albanian border. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Views Tornado Damage  
</P>
<P>
	TINKER AIR FORCE BASE, Okla. (AP) -- President Clinton today  
viewed wreckage left behind by killer tornadoes in Oklahoma and 
announced a $12 million program to provide temporary jobs to 
residents of the storm-ravaged area. He also said he would seek an 
additional $372 million from Congress for a federal disaster relief 
fund. After a half-hour helicopter tour of thousands of acres of 
twisted and shredded rubble, Clinton met survivors in Del City, 
Okla. ``I have been going to these scenes for 20 years and this is 
the most devastation I have ever seen,'' Clinton told residents. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Touts Work Flexibility Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican senator today promoted  
legislation that would give parents greater job flexibility to 
spend more time with their families. The so-called flex-time bill 
would allow working parents a chance to voluntarily rearrange their 
hours. If a mother wanted to tend to a sick child or attend a 
school event during her work hours, she could reschedule the missed 
time for a different day, Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., said in the 
weekly GOP radio address. 

</P>
<P>
	Rowdy U. of Akron Students Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Police in riot gear arrested 77 people and  
fired tear gas to disperse bottle-throwing students early this 
morning during an annual end-of-classes celebration by thousands of 
students at the University of Akron. Authorities said some students 
threw bottles at officers and their cars, while others ignited 
furniture and cheered as firefighters put out the flames. Police 
said they arrested 71 adults and six juveniles, mostly for 
disorderly conduct and underage drinking. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks 95, Heat 75  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell each scored 22  
points as the New York Knicks pounded the Miami Heat 95-75 to take 
Game 1 of their Eastern Conference, first-round series. The loss 
puts the top-seeded Heat in a daunting position, because now they 
must win at least one game at Madison Square Garden, where they're 
3-21. Game 2 will be Monday in Miami before the series shifts to 
New York. Miami shot just down 35 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Williams Tops Hingis To Reach Final  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Venus Williams defeated the world's top-ranked woman  
tennis player, Martina Hingis, 6-4, 1-6, 6-4 today to reach the 
Italian Open final for the second straight year. The older of the 
two Williams sisters moved into the finals to play Mary Pierce, who 
defeated Amelie Mauresmo of France 6-7 (1-7), 6-2, 6-4 in the day's 
first semifinal. Williams lost to Hingis in the Italian final last 
year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
