<DOCNO> APW19990508.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 11:51:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tornado Victims Pick Up the Pieces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMBER, Okla. (AP) -- She sat seven miles from home, watching TV  
reports of a spinning, swooping funnel dancing along the red-clay 
prairie. Then she heard where the twister was heading and her 
stomach tightened. She knew what was next. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just lost our house,'' Kim Kennedy calmly told her husband,  
Terry. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes later, the phone rang at her grandmother's house. It was  
a cousin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, 'Is it gone? Is it gone?' '' she recalls, her eyes  
widening in her freckled face as she remembers her question. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, the Kennedy home was gone, swept away by the wind.  
</P>
<P>
	One day, old-timers will tell tales of the Oklahoma twister of  
'99, the monster that killed 41 in this state alone, injured 
hundreds, and gobbled up thousands of homes, causing hundreds of 
millions of dollars in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kennedy family of Rural Route 1 will add their own chapter:  
Their home was among the first to fall. 
</P>
<P>
	It sat near the beginning of the tornado trail that ripped a  
60-mile gash across central Oklahoma, hurling propane tanks like 
soda cans, impaling cows on barbed wire, throwing horses onto 
parked cars, yanking a baby from his mother, lifting a man into 
soot-swirling skies and carrying him the length of four football 
fields. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Kennedys and their two children, this past week has been  
a time to seek comfort wherever they can; often it has come deep in 
mounds of mud, plaster and bricks. 
</P>
<P>
	There they have plucked out Bibles, an antique gold cameo brooch  
Kim inherited from her great-grandmother, a cherished salt shaker 
that belonged to her grandmother, even their 10-year-old daughter's 
knitting needle. They're still digging for the pocket-size Bible an 
uncle carried during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be OK,'' Mrs. Kennedy says, clutching a 'Ewe's  
Welcome' wooden sheep sign that once adorned their house. ``If I 
didn't know there was a God in control, you wouldn't see a smile on 
my face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They retrieved one more treasure: a photo in shattered glass of  
a second cousin, 18-month-old Blake Kennedy, killed in the federal 
building bombing four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cried,'' Mrs. Kennedy says, ``when I saw that.''  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Six miles north on the path of ruin, Don Smith searches for his  
own memory of the federal building. 
</P>
<P>
	For seven days in April 1995, the 37-year-old firefighter clawed  
and picked his way through rubble, pulling out victims of the 
Murrah building terrorist attack. He was given a granite chunk of 
the first floor as a memento. 
</P>
<P>
	It sat proudly atop his fireplace. But now his fireplace is  
gone. 
</P>
<P>
	So, too, are the walls, roof, floor, sinks, couch, closet,  
clothes, beds, stove, just about everything that belonged to the 
Smiths except their dazed Dalmatian -- who suffered a broken nose -- 
some photos and a few guitars he saved from his playing days in 
Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll humble you in a heartbeat,'' says his brother, Wes, who  
traveled from the Ozarks to lend a helping hand. ``One day you have 
everything in life. The next day you're out in the grass, kicking, 
trying to find something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith lost it all, but still is lucky.  
</P>
<P>
	He lives in Bridge Creek, a tiny community where 11 people died.  
It now looks like a Mad Max landscape: car doors twisted like taffy 
around trees, homes chewed up and spit out into heaps of metal and 
wood. 
</P>
<P>
	In two days, Smith buried 34 horses and too many dogs to  
remember on these windswept hills. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaning against his truck, stuffed with shopping bags of donated  
clothes and laundry baskets with soft drinks, toothpaste and cheese 
crackers, he ponders his fate. 
</P>
<P>
	``You do what everybody else does,'' he says. ``Sit down and cry  
awhile, then try to figure out what to do next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just strike one,'' he adds with a laugh. ``I think you  
get three in life -- don't you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Every now and then, a squeal of joy echoes through 130th Street  
in southwest Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	A dog is found. A bird's chirp is heard. Small blessings.  
</P>
<P>
	For Gary Welsh, it came Wednesday when he unearthed his  
next-door neighbor's parrot from the remains of their dining room. 
The cage was a bit twisted, the gray-blue bird a bit ruffled, but 
alive it was. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado veered northeast from the farmlands, barging across  
the city line, barreling into houses and garages, transforming the 
neighborhood into what looks like a war zone. 
</P>
<P>
	But as the days pass, humor survives among the ruins.  
</P>
<P>
	Angelo Martinez, 48, sits in his driveway, his house a heap of  
rubble behind him, as his insurance adjuster walks up and jokingly 
says: 
</P>
<P>
	``With a little duct tape, we can fix this up.''  
</P>
<P>
	Martinez is ready with a quick reply:  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll sell it to you for real cheap.''  
</P>
<P>
	Down the street, someone has scrawled across the front of  
another destroyed house: 
</P>
<P>
	``Fixer Upper. Make Offer.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Lovella Bahm doesn't live here anymore.  
</P>
<P>
	Oh Lord, how she would love to sleep in the same place she has  
for 34 years, but it is gone, along with many of her neighbors' 
places in Midwest City, at the northern edge of the storm's path. 
</P>
<P>
	But the world still turns. She discovered that in her mail this  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury duty notice was awaiting her.  
</P>
<P>
	She called to beg off, but was told to write a letter explaining  
her plight. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just corked me!'' she says.  
</P>
<P>
	``Look here,'' she told them, recalling her spiel with a wagging  
finger, her piercing blue eyes glimmering beneath her white sun 
hat. ``I don't have a house, a pencil, or chair to sit in. You're 
going to have to lay down on the ground and find me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Retirement wasn't supposed to be like this.  
</P>
<P>
	The 66-year-old grandmother planned to go with her husband on  
their annual trip to Padre Island, then spend the rest of her year 
surrounded by the comforts of home. But now her Jacuzzi is squashed 
by a Dumpster, her aviary of 100 cockatiels is nowhere to be found, 
her plate collection is shattered. 
</P>
<P>
	One moment she was huddling in the cellar with her grandson and  
his friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, poof! In a few seconds, like a wave of a diabolical magic  
wand, it was all gone. 
</P>
<P>
	Like so many other survivors along the tornado trail, Mrs. Bahm  
will rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
	But she's taking things slow and easy.  
</P>
<P>
	As the sun sets, she stands by the wooden gate that withstood  
the storm's fury and ponders the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to think positive,'' she says. ``Everything happens  
for the best. Well, I don't know about that now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then she pauses for a moment for a final thought.  
</P>
<P>
	``As time passes things will heal,'' she says. ``I'm sure I  
will, too.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 11:51:03 </DATE_TIME>
