<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A cold front pushed out into the Atlantic early today, leaving  
scattered rain along the East Coast and stronger storms across the 
Great Lakes. Rain and snow fell in the Northwest and Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 8 inches of snow were possible by tonight in the Cascades  
and Bitterroot mountains of the Northwest and northern Rockies. 
Rain was expected from Washington and Oregon east into the Dakotas. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong but scattered thunderstorms were forecast for parts of  
the East today as the front moves out to sea. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearing skies were expected in the South after damaging storms  
on Friday. In Bremen, Ga., about 50 miles of Atlanta, a tornado 
damaged trailers in a mobile home dealership. No injuries were 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Cloudy skies and showers were possible today in the Midwest and  
Great Lakes today. Fair and mostly dry conditions were predicted 
for the West, Southwest and southern Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature reported in the continental United  
States on Friday was 89 degrees at Punta Gorda, Fla. The low was 19 
at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 40s and 50s in the  
Northwest and northern Plains; the 60s and 70s in the Northeast, 
Midwest, Plains and West; and the 80s and 90s in the South and 
Southwest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
