<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rowdy Irishman Wins $100,000 Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Rowdy Irishman won his second  
consecutive $100,000 Iroquois Steeplechase on Saturday, beating 
Avanico by a neck at the end of a furious drive down the Percy 
Warner Park homestretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Chip Miller, who rode third-place finisher High Card, lodged a  
protest charging Rowdy Irishman and rider Vincent Marzullo with 
interference during the homestretch drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewards reviewed tapes for 15 minutes before affirming the  
victory for Rowdy Irishman, owned by Vesta Balestiere of Cashiers, 
N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Marzullo, of Franklin, Tenn., let High Card and Avanico have the  
lead for the first two turns of the three-mile run with 18 national 
hurdles. Going around the far turn the final time, the bay son of 
Erin's Isle was sent after the leaders and jumped the 18th fence on 
even terms with them. 
</P>
<P>
	With Rowdy Irishman on the inside, High Card in the middle,  
Avanico on the outside and the crowd of 30,000 roaring, the three 
horses matched strides for the final eighth of a mile. 
</P>
<P>
	The photo finish camera showed Rowdy Irishman the winner by a  
neck. Another neck separated Avanico and High Card. 
</P>
<P>
	The win for Rowdy Irishman was his fourth in a Grade I event. He  
has twice won the $150,000 American Grand National at Far Hills, 
N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwoods, ridden by Chip Miller, won the $50,000 co-feature, a  
three-mile race over post and rail fences. During that event, 
jockey Ellen Horner fell from Bit of Scotch when her saddle slipped 
over the first jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Horner was admitted to Saint Thomas Hospital and listed in  
critical condition with head injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no serious structural damage,'' Dr. J.W. Thomas Byrd  
said. ``That's an encouraging sign.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
