<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coach's Son Charged in Parrot Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin football coach Barry Alvarez's  
son faces criminal charges for breaking into a fraternity brother's 
room and microwaving a parrot to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have recommended charging Chad Alvarez, a senior at  
Wisconsin, with burglary and mistreating an animal. The 23-year-old 
Alvarez was arrested Friday after turning himself in. 
</P>
<P>
	He is expected to be arraigned Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Sigma Chi fraternity members found the dead parrot in the  
microwave last week while it was still operating, Madison police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cory Greenfield, a member of the fraternity, owned the parrot  
and said whoever killed ``Iago'' may have done so because he was 
angry about an e-mail that was passed around the fraternity house. 
</P>
<P>
	``He thought I was ridiculing him in front of the whole  
fraternity,'' Greenfield told The Capital Times of Madison. But 
Greenfield said ``there's no excuse when you put somebody's pet in 
the microwave and fry it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield would not refer to Alvarez by name, but he said  
whoever killed his parrot had confessed to the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield said the bird had a vocabulary of about 20 words.  
</P>
<P>
	If charged and convicted on both counts, Alvarez faces a maximum  
fine of $20,000 and 12-year jail sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Chad Alvarez pleaded no contest in April to first offense  
drunken driving, according to court records. 
</P>
<P>
	He was released Friday on a $500 signature bond.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990508.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:41:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets May Be Sold by Hess Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cablevision chairman Charles Dolan may get a  
third chance at owning an NFL franchise after two unsuccessful 
bids. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan is being mentioned among the potential buyers for the New  
York Jets following the death of owner Leon Hess. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess confided to some of his fellow NFL owners that he wanted  
the team sold rather than have his family run it after his death. 
</P>
<P>
	He was said to have been reluctant to leave the responsibility  
of ownership to his heirs, which include his son John, who 
succeeded his father as chairman of Amerada Hess Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan was an unsuccessful bidder for the Washington Redskins  
earlier this year and also failed to buy the Cleveland Browns 
expansion franchise last September. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners voted in favor of Alfred Lerner's $530 million offer for  
the Browns franchise over brothers Larry and Charles Dolan, who 
were teamed with Hall of Fame coach Don Shula and comedian Bill 
Cosby. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan was joined by New Jersey Devils owner John McMullen in his  
bid for the Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan may have had a problem even if he had been successful with  
either of those bids because of the NFL's cross ownership rule. 
</P>
<P>
	The league does not permit its owners to have a franchise in  
another sport except if that franchise is in the same market as the 
NFL franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Dolan's Cablevision owns the New York Knicks and New York  
Rangers, that would not be a problem should he decide to bid for 
the Jets. Nor would it be for McMullen. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan, anxious to expand his sports holdings, also reportedly  
made an offer for the New York Yankees recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Also mentioned in published reports as potential Jets' buyers  
were real estate and hotel-casino operator Donald Trump; Howard 
Milstein, who failed in a bid to buy the Redskins; Nelson 
Doubleday, part owner of the New York Mets; and Robert Tisch, part 
owner of the New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump would have to divest himself of his gambling casinos  
before becoming an owner in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Jets coach and general manager Bill Parcells has been  
mentioned as a likely point man for a group of investors, as well 
as Jets president Steve Gutman. 
</P>
<P>
	The franchise has been estimated to be worth about $500 million,  
according to sports finance experts quoted in Saturday's edition of 
The New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost will be considerably lower than the $800 million that  
the Redskins sold for, mainly because the Washington franchise 
included a new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services for Hess, who had been ill with a blood  
disorder for about a year, will be held Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess was an oil tycoon worth an estimated $720 million.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
