<DOCNO> APW19990508.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 14:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Suggests Settling Barney Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- A federal judge has recommended that the  
owners of Barney, the purple dinosaur loved by children, work out 
their differences with a company that rents and sells purple animal 
costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a case that ought to have been settled,'' U.S.  
District Judge Graham Mullen said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of the trial Friday, Mullen announced that he was  
taking the case under advisement. He said it could take him some 
time to issue a ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Barney's owner, Lyons Partnership of Richardson, Texas, sued  
Morris Costumes in 1997, accusing the Charlotte company of 
copyright and trademark infringement for renting and selling purple 
animal costumes that look like Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar lawsuits targeting the Barney look-alikes have been  
filed across the country, but this is the first case to go to 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barney's young fans accept him as a `real' best friend, and  
trust him completely,'' Lyons Partnership said in a statement. 
``Many of these very vulnerable children have been shocked and 
disappointed by seeing someone in a bogus `Barney' costume behaving 
rudely, smoking, drinking, or otherwise behaving in ways they know 
are not appropriate for Barney.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Morris Costumes, one of the nation's largest costume  
distributors, say there has been no infringement. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris Costumes' lawyer, Jay Bilas, told Mullen that parents  
renting the costumes for their children's birthday parties knew 
they weren't Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons Partnership is seeking a court-ordered injunction  
preventing Morris Costumes from renting or selling the costumes 
resembling Barney. Barney's owner also wants $300,000 for what it 
calls willful infringement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
