<DOCNO> APW19990508.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:42:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hart Upset by Royals Protest Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Sorry, Royals fans. John Hart doesn't feel your  
pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland's general manager has heard reports that the Indians,  
like the Yankees before them, will be greeted by protesters when 
they visit Kansas City next month. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of 3,000 Royals supporters, upset with a growing chasm  
in baseball's economic system that pits big-money franchises like 
New York, Cleveland and Baltimore -- all with payrolls above $68 
million -- against Kansas City's paltry $24 million, wore T-shirts 
reading ``$hare the Wealth'' and walked out of Kauffman Stadium 
during the fourth inning of a recent game against the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart has heard the fans are planning a similar welcome for the  
Indians when they go to Kansas City for a four-game series 
beginning June 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're on the list as one of the teams to be protested, I  
think it's an absolute joke,'' Hart said. ``Because in our 
situation, we are truly the same kind of market as Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just that we've had a plan and gone about it and our fans  
support us and our community supports us. We don't have any 
ancillary extra dollars coming in from television. We've been very 
creative and very aggressive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where were they six years or seven years ago when they were  
winning and spending (former owner) Ewing Kauffman's money and not 
developing a plan and paying attention to what was going on? The 
guy dies and says, 'Here's the money, go ahead and support the 
team.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing rankles Hart more than when the Indians are lumped  
together with the big-market, big-money Yankees and Dodgers, teams 
who draw much of their revenue from large local television 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't long ago that Cleveland was baseball's sorriest city  
with a crumbling stadium, low attendance figures and a skimpy 
payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were no protests in Cleveland when we had two or three  
thousand at the game and we were going into Toronto with an $8 
million payroll to their $51 million,'' Hart said. ``We just said, 
'Hey, let's fix it. Let's not let somebody else do it. Let's fix it 
ourselves.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart understands there is a disparity issue in baseball, but  
he's quick to point out that spending money isn't necessarily the 
quickest way to the top. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no guarantees,'' he said. ``The Dodgers have had a  
lot of money for four years, and they haven't been in it. Colorado 
has had a lot of money, and they haven't been in it. Texas has been 
in and out, in and out.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
