<HEADLINE> Mutiny 2, Fire 1 (so) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Scott Garlick stopped all five shots and R.T.  
Moore scored the lone shootout goal as the Tampa Bay Mutiny won 
their third straight game, a 2-1 victory over the Chicago Fire 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore converted his first career shootout attempt in the fourth  
round. Garlick made the slim lead hold up when he stopped Jerzy 
Podbrozny on Chicago's final chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams were missing key players because of suspensions or  
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutiny midfielder Carlos Valderrama and Chicago defender Lubos  
Kubik, the 1998 MLS defender of the year, served suspensions for 
incurring red cards. Fire forward Ante Razov, the league's leading 
scorer with six goals and three assists, sprained his right ankle 
May 1 and is expected to miss 3-4 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fire went up 1-0 when Josh Wolff scored his third goal in  
the sixth minute. The forward beat Garlick to a pass from Roman 
Kosecki and scored from 10 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay tied the game on Jefferson Gottardi's fourth goal  
during the 57th minute. From near the left post, Gottardi 
redirected Mauricio Ramos' shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramos set a Mutiny record by picking up an assist in four  
straight games. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago goalkeeper Zach Thornton preserved the regulation tie,  
robbing Pete Marino from in close with just over two minutes left 
to play. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fire lost two players during the game. Team captain Peter  
Nowak departed in the 71st minute with a left calf strain and C.J. 
Brown left with cramps in the 58th minute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
