<HEADLINE> Murray Bros. Now on Opposite Sides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMAR, Norway (AP) -- Brothers Bryan and Terry Murray, who work  
together all year for the good of the Florida Panthers, will have 
different agendas Sunday when Canada plays the United States in the 
second round of the World Hockey Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Murray coaches the U.S. team, while Bryan is Team Canada's  
general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The two are taking a break from their duties with the Panthers.  
Terry is the coach of the NHL team, and Bryan, as the club's 
general manager, is his brother's boss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been through this many times: Washington-Detroit,  
Philadelphia-Florida,'' Terry said, referring to the times the two 
brothers worked for different NHL teams. ``The first time there was 
a lot of attention, a lot of interviews, a lot of distraction for 
the two teams that were playing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't affect our relationship,'' Terry said. ``When we  
get back to work (with the Panthers) nothing will have changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't mean much, it's the Canadians playing the United  
States. That's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Terry, nationality had little to do with accepting the  
position of head coach for the American team. He has lived in the 
United States for 30 years and has been a U.S. citizen for about 18 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	It had more to do with opportunity knocking.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I had been asked by Canada, even this year, I would gladly  
have gone. I would have loved to have come,'' Terry Murray said. 
``But my phone never rang. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity came from the U.S. team and I had the U.S.  
passport. I didn't want to pass up the opportunity. It's a once in 
a lifetime chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Older brother Bryan agreed. He, too, jumped at the chance to  
join the Canadian team. 
</P>
<P>
	And it wasn't the first time.  
</P>
<P>
	He was an assistant coach for Canada at the 1990 world  
championships when the team got into the semifinals where they lost 
to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime you get the opportunity and are invited to represent  
your country it's an exciting challenge,'' said Bryan Murray, 56. 
``It's a very competitive tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While it's his first time as a coach at a major international  
tournament, Terry is not feeling any particular pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though at the last world championships, a quickly-assembled  
group of mismatched American players went crashing out in the 
opening round. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any anxiety? Not for me, not at all,'' said Terry. ``The past  
has nothing to do with what's going on in the future. It's a new 
year. The attitude is different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the team has managed to get past the preliminary round  
this year, routing Japan 7-1 and defeating Austria 5-2, it suffered 
4-3 losses to Olympic champions Czech Republic and Olympic bronze 
medal winner Finland. The latter in its second-round opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada, the 1997 world champions, opened their second round  
campaign with an 8-2 win over Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	In other second round play Sunday, the Czechs will face Slovakia  
while Finland, the losing finalists to Sweden last year, will play 
Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champions Sweden will meet Russia,  
</P>
</TEXT>
