<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 14:52:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Gives Talk, Despite Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLINTON, Iowa (AP) -- Democratic presidential hopeful Bill  
Bradley delivered the commencement address as planned Saturday at 
Mount St. Clare College despite a call from a national Roman 
Catholic group that wanted his invitation withdrawn. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falls Church, Va.-based Cardinal Newman Society had asked  
college president James Ross to cancel Bradley's invitation because 
he supports abortion rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``I recognize that some people disagree on certain issues, but  
for me, I have tremendous respect for ... Mount St. Clare, for the 
leadership here at this institution and for the young people who 
are graduating today,'' Bradley said in an interview before 
speaking to the 102 graduates at the school's 69th commencement 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	A former senator from New Jersey, Bradley said he understood why  
the Cardinal Newman Society objected to his appearance. The 
organization had asked 10 Catholic colleges this spring to cancel 
invitations to speakers who support abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a country that has free speech, and people can express  
their views, and that's fine,'' said Bradley, who has taught at 
Notre Dame, the nation's most prominent Catholic university. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley did not address the controversy during a 15-minute  
speech to about 1,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he talked about the ``horrific tragedy'' of the  
Littleton, Colo., high school shooting on April 20 in which 13 
students and a teacher died. 
</P>
<P>
	Too many parents, he said, were becoming too busy in their own  
lives to pay attention to their children. He said the ``scourge of 
school shootings'' around the country in recent years have killed a 
total of 28 people while injuring 71. 
</P>
<P>
	``Children's values are shaped as much by television, the  
shopping malls, the video games as they are shaped by the 
parents,'' Bradley said. ``Something is wrong when parents are so 
out of touch they don't know that bombs are being built under their 
own roof. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must take responsibility for the society that are children  
live in. We must teach them the sense of right and wrong, good and 
evil. These are the seeds of conscience, and we must do what we can 
to help them grow,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mount St. Clare officials never gave any thought to canceling  
Bradley's appearance, Ross said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a Franciscan college, it's important for us to expose our  
students to all varieties of groups of people,'' he said. ``In my 
situation, I do have a difference of opinion on the issue. I have 
always been strongly in favor of the pro-life aspect of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``But again, Mr. Bradley has done so many different things for  
our society and what he stands for,'' Ross said. ``The college does 
not endorse any particular viewpoint of any of its speakers. We did 
not have any thought of rescinding the invitation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
