<DOCNO> APW19990508.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 05:54:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Scrutinizing AT&AMP;T-MediaOne Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T's plan to buy MediaOne, a deal that would  
create the nation's largest cable TV company and provider of 
high-speed cable Internet services, ``warrants very careful 
scrutiny,'' the FCC's chief said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The $58 billion deal's size, complexity and its potential reach  
into American homes must be studied, Federal Communications 
Commission Chairman Bill Kennard said in his first comment on the 
matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement reached Tuesday, AT&AMP;T would acquire the  
nation's fourth-largest cable TV company, MediaOne, and its 5 
million cable TV customers. AT&AMP;T also would acquire MediaOne's 25 
percent stake in cable systems owned by Time Warner Inc., the 
nation's largest cable TV company. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, which recently took over the nation's No. 2 cable TV  
company, Tele-Communications Inc., would become the nation's 
largest cable TV provider, directly or indirectly owning cable TV 
systems that reach two-thirds of U.S. homes, government officials 
estimated Friday. AT&AMP;T, already the country's biggest long-distance 
company, considers the two-thirds figure overstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Importantly, those cable deals as well as other cable alliances  
would give AT&AMP;T direct links to carry telephone, television, 
Internet services and interactive entertainment into U.S. homes. 
Without the links, AT&AMP;T would have to rely on other companies, 
notably its rival Baby Bells, to have a direct pathway into 
customers' homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Cleland, director of Legg Mason's Precursor Group,  
comparing Kennard's statement with his positive comments on the 
AT&AMP;T-TCI deal, interpreted the chairman's comment on the proposed 
merger as significant. ``He gave a positive signal when AT&AMP;T and 
TCI was announced,'' Cleland said. ``This time the tone and words 
are quite different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, both Cleland and AT&AMP;T believe the deal will be approved  
by the FCC. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, AT&AMP;T would acquire MediaOne's 50 percent  
management interest in cable Internet services provider Road Runner 
-- the biggest competitor to At Home, in which AT&AMP;T now has a 
controlling stake through its takeover of TCI. 
</P>
<P>
	At Home and Road Runner are the two main providers of Internet,  
data and other information that cable customers can obtain using 
high-speed cable TV lines and special cable modems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers will lose all hope of choice,'' said Mark Cooper of  
the Consumer Federation of America, which wants the FCC to block 
the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's deal with MediaOne is intensifying calls by America  
Online, consumer groups and some of the nation's Baby Bells that 
the government force AT&AMP;T to give all companies access to its 
high-speed cable TV lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of its size and reach and the many novel legal and  
policy issues involved, this proposed merger warrants very careful 
scrutiny,'' Kennard said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	While the deal holds the promise of helping AT&AMP;T crack open the  
Baby Bells' local telephone monopoly -- something attractive to 
Washington lawmakers and regulators -- its potential reach over 
cable TV customers makes some policy-makers nervous. Senate 
hearings on the merger will be next month. 
</P>
<P>
	In a race against the nation's five Baby Bells, wireless  
companies and satellite providers, AT&AMP;T aims to use cable as its 
foundation to become a dominant national player in providing 
telecommunications and entertainment services. It does not own any 
of the telephone connection lines into people's homes. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC staff are now trying to sort through the many issues the  
merger raises. They include the deal's effects on the ability of 
new cable TV networks to be carried on AT&AMP;T-owned or -controlled 
cable TV systems; rivals' ability to gain access to cable TV 
programming; and competition for, and consumers' access to, 
high-speed cable Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	And another big issue looming for the proposed deal: compliance  
with any new federal rules that may be put in place to restrict the 
number of cable customers a single company can control. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
