<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 08:31:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Undeclared but Leading the Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- A month from his debut as a presidential  
campaigner, Gov. George W. Bush professes amazement at his ranking 
atop the Republican field in a race he plans to run on his terms 
and on his timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	He knows what's coming when he takes the road from Texas. He  
stayed put to deal with the business of the state Legislature, 
which adjourns at the end of the month. So Republican leaders came 
to him, 150 or more, to see, hear and endorse the man at the top of 
the preseason polls for the GOP nomination, and for the 2000 
presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, he talks in minute  
detail of state legislation, but he is purposefully vague on 
national issues. ``I know what I believe, and I know what I will 
fight for,'' he said. ``I will have a tax plan. I'll have plans on 
various issues which we will lay out on my timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very long and arduous road, as you know, and the  
temptation's going to be for people to want to know it immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``What are you going to do on this, what are you going to do on  
that? 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be specific in some areas and in some areas, I'll hold my  
fire, so I'll have something to say over the course of the fall and 
the winter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That will intensify the pressure, the questions, the criticism  
from other candidates and from commentators for a detailed platform 
from Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	It will come in a rush when Bush begins his active campaign next  
month. He's booked to begin with two private fund-raising events on 
the way to a day of campaigning in Iowa on June 12. He's to be in 
New Hampshire on June 14 and 15. After opening in the small states 
that hold the initial contests of the 2000 primary season, Bush is 
booked for a campaign tour in the biggest, California, in late 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	Current planning puts him on the campaign road for two weeks in  
June, two weeks in July and 17 days in August. No gradual glide 
path into the campaign for Bush; he begins running in a rush, with 
a media crowd certain. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know there are going to be a lot of diversions,'' Bush says.  
``There'll be moments of stress, and I know that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Make that months of stress. There is no political role more  
intense and demanding than running for president, especially for 
the candidate in front. Every public pronouncement is sifted, every 
slip magnified. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush saw it in his father's presidential campaigns, the winner  
in 1988, the loser in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	And front-runners have fallen before. Gov. George Romney of  
Michigan led in advance but collapsed as a candidate in 1968. Sen. 
Edmund S. Muskie of Maine was the faraway Democratic favorite in 
1972, until he faltered and failed in the primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job is to stay focused on why people should be for me,''  
says Bush, who does not yet call his candidacy by name. He's still 
exploring, undeclared. But that's only timing. He's raised $7.6 
million, expects to at least double that by midsummer. There are 
about 35 people in his Austin political headquarters, and they're 
hiring. More than half the 32 Republican governors are backing him, 
as are about 100 GOP members of Congress. ``We've got the 
beginnings of a good political operation in some of the states,'' 
he says. 
</P>
<P>
	All with the candidate at a distance. His father became  
president in 1989 after a long apprenticeship in government that 
began long before his eight years as vice president. The son's 
campaign standing comes after one term as governor and landslide 
re-election in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I'm amazed,'' Bush says. ``... I know I've got a lot of  
work to do after the session's over to go to these states where I 
haven't been ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	At home, he's studying national policy issues, meeting regularly  
with a team of advisers with Washington know-how. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that one of the things I'm good at is campaigning -- I  
like people a lot -- I like to shake hands and I like to look people 
in the eye and say I'd like for you to hear me and help me out,'' 
Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	But that kind of one-on-one campaign is difficult if not  
impossible in the era of nonstop television, boom microphones, 
crowds of reporters, Secret Service security. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to go shake those hands,'' Bush said. ``It's going to  
be interesting to see how we can accomplish that.'' That's been his 
strength in Texas campaigns, not the stump speech to the crowd. 
There will have to be more of the latter now, and more television 
campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	All to put him to the special tests of the leader. ``I know the  
expectations are high,'' Bush says. ``As my daughter said, 'Dad, 
you're not nearly as cool as people think.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	He's about to begin finding out.  
</P>
<P>
                           	 *--------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
