<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 05:54:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Atlantic-GTE Merger Cleared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department approved a merger plan  
that would create the nation's largest local phone company, but 
only on condition that Bell Atlantic and GTE sell off overlapping 
wireless mobile systems in nine states, Justice officials said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed Bell Atlantic-GTE merger would be even bigger than  
the planned merger of regional Bell companies SBC Communications 
Inc. and Ameritech Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission is now reviewing the plan  
and has raised some concerns involving GTE's Internet and 
long-distance holdings. Several state public utility commissions 
also must approve the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	To win Justice Department approval, Bell Atlantic and GTE agreed  
to divest themselves of overlapping wireless systems in 65 markets 
in a consent decree filed Friday in federal court in Washington. 
Justice officials said the agreement would resolve their concerns 
that the deal as originally planned would substantially reduce 
competition, lower quality and raise prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The decree won't become final until a judge approves it.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the largest divestiture packages involving a  
merger ever required by the department's Antitrust Division,'' 
officials said in a written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wireless mobile telephones are increasingly becoming an  
important part of everyday life for an ever-growing number of 
Americans, and we rely on competition to ensure that customers get 
the lowest prices as well as features and rate plans that best fit 
their plans,'' said Joel I. Klein, assistant attorney general in 
charge of the antitrust division. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department said the original plan would have led to  
a loss of head-to-head competition in wireless mobile telephone 
services in 65 markets that have a total population of more than 25 
million. The divestitures would include the major metropolitan 
areas of Chicago, Houston, Richmond, Va., and Tampa, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``In four of the markets, Bell Atlantic has ownership interest  
in one cellular system and GTE has an ownership interest in the 
other,'' the department's statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In 46 of these markets, GTE has an ownership interest in one  
of the cellular systems and PrimeCo -- a firm that is 50 percent 
owned by Bell Atlantic -- owns one of the personal communications 
services wireless businesses,'' it said. ``In addition, GTE is 
acquiring 15 cellular systems from Ameritech in a recently 
announced acquisition, and PrimeCo owns the PCS wireless business 
in those 15 markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic's general counsel said the company knew it would  
have to deal with the companies' wireless overlaps when it 
announced the merger in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decree gives us full flexibility to clear wireless  
conflicts by disposing of either cellular or PCS properties,'' said 
James R. Young, who also is a Bell Atlantic executive vice 
president. ``We have time to resolve wireless conflicts in an 
orderly way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decree calls on Bell Atlantic and GTE to complete  
divestitures of overlapping wireless businesses they either already 
own or will own within 180 days of closing the deal. If they fail 
to do this, the businesses must be turned over to a trustee chosen 
by the Justice Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
